{"title_page": "George Buza", "text_new": "{{short description|American-Canadian actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = George Buza\n| image = \n| alt =\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|1|07}}\n| birth_place = [[Cleveland, Ohio]], U.S.\n| Residence   = [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| other_names = George Busa\n| years_active = 1975\u2013present\n| occupation  = Actor\n}}\n\n'''George Buza''' (born January 7, 1949) is an American-Canadian actor who is best known for voicing [[Beast (comics)|Beast]] in the ''[[X-Men (TV series)|X-Men Animated Series]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn in [[Cleveland, Ohio]], he moved to [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada, as a young man and became a [[Canadians|Canadian citizen]] in 1998.\n\n==Career==\nGeorge Buza played Turner Edison on ''[[Maniac Mansion (TV series)|Maniac Mansion]]'' for the entirety of its 1990-1993 run on [[YTV (TV channel)|YTV]] and [[The Family Channel (American TV network, founded 1980)|The Family Channel]]. He also had a role on the ''[[Red Green Show]]''. He appeared as Chief Jake McKenna multiple times in the TV series ''[[Honey, I Shrunk the Kids: The TV Show]]''. In addition, he portrayed Doubar, the older brother of Sinbad, in ''[[The Adventures of Sinbad]]'' syndicated TV series, as well as a recurring role on the syndicated ''[[Mutant X (TV series)|Mutant X]]''. George was also in episode 11 of TVOntario's ''[[Read All About It!|Read All About It]]'', and played Buck Norris on ''[[The Strain (TV series)|The Strain]]''. He was one of the Kzamm tribe in ''[[Quest for Fire (film)]].''\n\nHe also makes a small appearance as a trucker in 2000's [[X-Men (film)|''X-Men'' movie]], and a biker in George Romero's ''[[Diary of The Dead]]''. He played Stuckmore in 2002's ''[[Men With Brooms]]''. George Buza also played Lenny \"The Brain\" Lepinski in the Quebec-Ontario TV show called \"The Last Chapter\". He also played [[Santa Claus|Santa]], the character that fought [[Krampus]] in the horror movie ''[[A Christmas Horror Story]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://horrornews.net/102729/interview-george-buza-a-christmas-horror-story/ |title=Interview: George Buza (A Christmas Horror Story) |first=Janel |last=Spiegel |publisher=Horrornews.net |date=October 15, 2015 |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://theactionelite.com/2015/09/interview-with-george-buza/ |title=Interview with George Buza |work= The Action Elite |date=September 30, 2015 |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Voice work===\nGeorge is probably best known for voicing [[Beast (comics)|Beast]] in the ''[[X-Men Animated Series]]''. He also reprised the role in the video games ''[[X-Men: Children of the Atom (video game)|X-Men: Children of the Atom]]'' and both ''[[X-Men: Mutant Academy]]'' games. He also narrated the opening title and voiced several characters in ''[[Jayce and the Wheeled Warriors]]''.\n\nGeorge has also provided character voices in many animated TV series.<ref name=\"btva\">{{cite web |url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/George-Buza/ |title=George Buza |work=Behind the Voice Actors |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref> He voiced Grandpa Granger in the English dub of ''[[Beyblade]]'', Chief Chirpa on ''[[Star Wars: Ewoks]]'', and additional roles in ''[[Star Wars: Droids]]'', ''[[The Busy World of Richard Scarry]]'', ''[[Mythic Warriors: Guardians of the Legend]]'', ''[[The Neverending Story (TV series)|The Neverending Story]]'', ''[[Babar (TV series)|Babar]]'', ''[[Hammerman]]'', ''[[Grossology (TV series)|Grossology]]'', ''[[Iggy Arbuckle]]'', ''[[Dog City]]'', ''[[Pecola]]'', ''[[Monster Force]]'', ''[[Franny's Feet]]'' ''[[Starlink: Battle for Atlas]]'' and ''[[Tales from the Cryptkeeper]]''.\n\nHe also provided his voice in the English dub of ''[[Medabots]]'' and ''[[Power Stone]]'' video games.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Television===\n*''[[Beyblade]]'' - Grandpa Granger (English Dub) <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''Franny\u2019s Feet'' - Grandpa <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[Dog City]]'' - Steven <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[Little Bear (TV series)]]'' - Rusty Bear\n*''[[Grossology (TV series)|Grossology]]'' - Sloppy Joe, Frankenbooger <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[Maniac Mansion (TV series)|Maniac Mansion]]'' - Turner Edison\n*''[[Mythic Warriors: Guardians of the Legend]]'' - King Minos, Gorgus <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[The Neverending Story (TV series)|The Neverending Story]]'' - Ogre, East Wind <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[Tales from the Cryptkeeper]]'' - William, Mr. Armstrong <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[Power Stone]]'' - Kraken (English Dub)\n*''[[Sidekick (TV series)|''Sidekick'' (TV series)]]'' - Sheriff Marshall (episode: \"Ye Old Sidekick Village\") <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[Spider-Man (1994 TV series)|Spider-Man]]'' - [[Beast (comics)|Beast]]\n*''[[Star Wars: Droids]]'' - Additional voices\n*''[[Star Wars: Ewoks]]'' - Chief Chirpa\n*''[[X-Men (TV series)|X-Men Animated Series]]'' - Beast\n\n===Film===\n*''[[A Christmas Horror Story]]'' - [[Santa Claus]]/Norman\n*''[[Diary of The Dead]]'' - Tattooed Biker\n*''[[The Brain (1988 film)]]'' - Varna\n*''Elliot: The Littlest Reindeer'' - Santa Claus <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''Fish N Chips: The Movie'' - Chipsus Barbotus, The Admiral <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[X-Men (film)|X-Men]]'' - Trucker\n\n===Video games===\n*''[[Marvel vs. Capcom 2: New Age of Heroes]]'' - [[Colossus (comics)|Colossus]]\n*''[[Starlink: Battle for Atlas]]'' - Kharl Zeon <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[X-Men: Children of the Atom (video game)|X-Men: Children of the Atom]]'' - Announcer, Colossus, [[Juggernaut (comics)|Juggernaut]], [[Omega Red]], [[Magneto (Marvel Comics)|Magneto]]\n*''[[X-Men: Mutant Academy 2]]'' - [[Beast (comics)|Beast]].\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nIn 1992 he was nominated for a [[Gemini Award]] for Best Performance in a Comedy Program or Series (Individual or Ensemble) for ''[[Maniac Mansion (TV series)|Maniac Mansion]]''. He was nominated again in 2001 for Best Ensemble Performance in a Comedy Program or Series for ''[[The Red Green Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.academy.ca:80/gemini16/noms/allnoms.html |title=16th Annual Gemini Awards: All Nominees |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010919102646/http://www.academy.ca/gemini16/noms/allnoms.html |archive-date=September 19, 2001 |publisher=Academy of Canadian Cinema & Television }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0125579}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buza, George}}\n[[Category:Canadian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male video game actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Toronto]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American-Canadian actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = George Buza\n| image = \n| alt =\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1949|1|07}}\n| birth_place = [[Cleveland, Ohio]], U.S.\n| Residence   = [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| other_names = George Busa\n| years_active = 1975\u2013present\n| occupation  = Actor\n}}\n\n'''George Buza''' (born January 7, 1949) is an American-Canadian actor who is best known for voicing [[Beast (comics)|Beast]] in the ''[[X-Men (TV series)|X-Men Animated Series]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn in [[Cleveland, Ohio]], he moved to [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada, as a young man and became a [[Canadians|Canadian citizen]] in 1998.\n\n==Career==\nGeorge Buza played Turner Edison on ''[[Maniac Mansion (TV series)|Maniac Mansion]]'' for the entirety of its 1990-1993 run on [[YTV (TV channel)|YTV]] and [[The Family Channel (United States)|The Family Channel]]. He also had a role on the ''[[Red Green Show]]''. He appeared as Chief Jake McKenna multiple times in the TV series ''[[Honey, I Shrunk the Kids: The TV Show]]''. In addition, he portrayed Doubar, the older brother of Sinbad, in ''[[The Adventures of Sinbad]]'' syndicated TV series, as well as a recurring role on the syndicated ''[[Mutant X (TV series)|Mutant X]]''. George was also in episode 11 of TVOntario's ''[[Read All About It!|Read All About It]]'', and played Buck Norris on ''[[The Strain (TV series)|The Strain]]''. He was one of the Kzamm tribe in ''[[Quest for Fire (film)]].''\n\nHe also makes a small appearance as a trucker in 2000's [[X-Men (film)|''X-Men'' movie]], and a biker in George Romero's ''[[Diary of The Dead]]''. He played Stuckmore in 2002's ''[[Men With Brooms]]''. George Buza also played Lenny \"The Brain\" Lepinski in the Quebec-Ontario TV show called \"The Last Chapter\". He also played [[Santa Claus|Santa]], the character that fought [[Krampus]] in the horror movie ''[[A Christmas Horror Story]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://horrornews.net/102729/interview-george-buza-a-christmas-horror-story/ |title=Interview: George Buza (A Christmas Horror Story) |first=Janel |last=Spiegel |publisher=Horrornews.net |date=October 15, 2015 |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://theactionelite.com/2015/09/interview-with-george-buza/ |title=Interview with George Buza |work= The Action Elite |date=September 30, 2015 |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Voice work===\nGeorge is probably best known for voicing [[Beast (comics)|Beast]] in the ''[[X-Men Animated Series]]''. He also reprised the role in the video games ''[[X-Men: Children of the Atom (video game)|X-Men: Children of the Atom]]'' and both ''[[X-Men: Mutant Academy]]'' games. He also narrated the opening title and voiced several characters in ''[[Jayce and the Wheeled Warriors]]''.\n\nGeorge has also provided character voices in many animated TV series.<ref name=\"btva\">{{cite web |url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/George-Buza/ |title=George Buza |work=Behind the Voice Actors |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref> He voiced Grandpa Granger in the English dub of ''[[Beyblade]]'', Chief Chirpa on ''[[Star Wars: Ewoks]]'', and additional roles in ''[[Star Wars: Droids]]'', ''[[The Busy World of Richard Scarry]]'', ''[[Mythic Warriors: Guardians of the Legend]]'', ''[[The Neverending Story (TV series)|The Neverending Story]]'', ''[[Babar (TV series)|Babar]]'', ''[[Hammerman]]'', ''[[Grossology (TV series)|Grossology]]'', ''[[Iggy Arbuckle]]'', ''[[Dog City]]'', ''[[Pecola]]'', ''[[Monster Force]]'', ''[[Franny's Feet]]'' ''[[Starlink: Battle for Atlas]]'' and ''[[Tales from the Cryptkeeper]]''.\n\nHe also provided his voice in the English dub of ''[[Medabots]]'' and ''[[Power Stone]]'' video games.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Television===\n*''[[Beyblade]]'' - Grandpa Granger (English Dub) <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''Franny\u2019s Feet'' - Grandpa <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[Dog City]]'' - Steven <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[Little Bear (TV series)]]'' - Rusty Bear\n*''[[Grossology (TV series)|Grossology]]'' - Sloppy Joe, Frankenbooger <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[Maniac Mansion (TV series)|Maniac Mansion]]'' - Turner Edison\n*''[[Mythic Warriors: Guardians of the Legend]]'' - King Minos, Gorgus <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[The Neverending Story (TV series)|The Neverending Story]]'' - Ogre, East Wind <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[Tales from the Cryptkeeper]]'' - William, Mr. Armstrong <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[Power Stone]]'' - Kraken (English Dub)\n*''[[Sidekick (TV series)|''Sidekick'' (TV series)]]'' - Sheriff Marshall (episode: \"Ye Old Sidekick Village\") <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[Spider-Man (1994 TV series)|Spider-Man]]'' - [[Beast (comics)|Beast]]\n*''[[Star Wars: Droids]]'' - Additional voices\n*''[[Star Wars: Ewoks]]'' - Chief Chirpa\n*''[[X-Men (TV series)|X-Men Animated Series]]'' - Beast\n\n===Film===\n*''[[A Christmas Horror Story]]'' - [[Santa Claus]]/Norman\n*''[[Diary of The Dead]]'' - Tattooed Biker\n*''[[The Brain (1988 film)]]'' - Varna\n*''Elliot: The Littlest Reindeer'' - Santa Claus <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''Fish N Chips: The Movie'' - Chipsus Barbotus, The Admiral <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[X-Men (film)|X-Men]]'' - Trucker\n\n===Video games===\n*''[[Marvel vs. Capcom 2: New Age of Heroes]]'' - [[Colossus (comics)|Colossus]]\n*''[[Starlink: Battle for Atlas]]'' - Kharl Zeon <ref name=\"btva\"/>\n*''[[X-Men: Children of the Atom (video game)|X-Men: Children of the Atom]]'' - Announcer, Colossus, [[Juggernaut (comics)|Juggernaut]], [[Omega Red]], [[Magneto (Marvel Comics)|Magneto]]\n*''[[X-Men: Mutant Academy 2]]'' - [[Beast (comics)|Beast]].\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nIn 1992 he was nominated for a [[Gemini Award]] for Best Performance in a Comedy Program or Series (Individual or Ensemble) for ''[[Maniac Mansion (TV series)|Maniac Mansion]]''. He was nominated again in 2001 for Best Ensemble Performance in a Comedy Program or Series for ''[[The Red Green Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.academy.ca:80/gemini16/noms/allnoms.html |title=16th Annual Gemini Awards: All Nominees |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010919102646/http://www.academy.ca/gemini16/noms/allnoms.html |archive-date=September 19, 2001 |publisher=Academy of Canadian Cinema & Television }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0125579}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buza, George}}\n[[Category:Canadian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male video game actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Toronto]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Gonnym", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:update links after RM", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Buza"}
{"title_page": "Valery Mikhailovich Didula", "text_new": "'''Valery Mikhailovich Didula''' ([[Belarus|Belorussian]]. Valersky Mikhailovich Dzidzyulya, January 24, 1969, Grodno, Belorussian SSR, USSR) - Soviet and Belarusian guitar virtuoso, composer, arranger, music producer, leader of the DiDuLa band.<ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|title=\u2013 Russian Guitar Virtuoso to Perform in New York|url=https://voicesofny.org/2013/01/russian-guitar-virtuoso-to-perform-in-new-york/|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-13|publication-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pravda.ru/culture/1158607-music/|title=\u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044c\u044e \u0441 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043c, \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043e\u0437\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043c, \u0443\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u043c \u0433\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043c \u0414\u0438\u0414\u044e\u041b\u0435\u0439|first=\u0410\u043d\u0436\u0435\u043b\u0430|last=\u042f\u043a\u0443\u0431\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f|date=May 29, 2013|website=\u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u0430.\u0420\u0443}}</ref> Performs [[Folk music|folk]] and [[Fusion (music)|fusion]] music with a new age influence.\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| name             = DiDuLa\n| birth_date       = 24 January 1970\n| birth_place      = Grodno, Belorussian SSR, {{USSR}}\n| instrument       = Classical guitar, flamenco guitar\n| genre            = pop folk, new flamenco, new age\n| years_active     = 2000 - present\n| website          = www.didula.com\n| image            = \u0414\u0438\u0414\u044e\u041b\u044f.jpg\n}}\n\n== Biography ==\nDidula<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://24smi.org/celebrity/4706-valerii-didiulia.html|title=\u0414\u0438\u0434\u044e\u043b\u044f|website=24SMI}}</ref> was born in a family of music lovers. The first guitar was given to him by his mother at the age of five.<ref name=\":02\" /> He began to practice and quickly mastered it. At sixteen he wrote his first compositions.<ref name=\"abc\">{{cite web|title=Didjulja|url=http://www.abc-guitars.com/pages/didjulja.htm|website=abc-guitars.com|language=fr|publication-date=}}</ref> He later got a job as a third guitar ensemble \"Scarlet Dawns\" led by Nikolai Khitrik. Concerts were held in different cities, collective farms and state farms, and then in&nbsp; restaurants. After graduation school, he entered the radio engineering school<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc-guitars.com/pages/didjulja.htm|title=\u0418\u043b\u043b\u044e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0431\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044c|website=www.abc-guitars.com|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\n== Confirmation of his style ==\nAfter the collapse of the ensemble, Didula took up sound engineering in the Grodno song and dance ensemble \u201cWhite Dew\u201d, where mostly Polish, Belarusian, Ukrainian, gypsy folk dances and motifs played, sang and danced.<ref name=\"peo\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.peoples.ru/art/music/guitars/didula/index.html|title=\u0411\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f \u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0414\u0438\u0414\u044e\u041b\u044f|website=www.peoples.ru}}</ref> As part of this team, Didula first went on tour in Europe - in [[Spain]], [[Italy]], [[Poland]], [[Switzerland]], [[France]], [[Germany]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\"peo\"/> In [[Spain]], he became acquainted with the [[flamenco]] style - the traditional Spanish music and dance style, which influenced its final formation (Didula's work traces some passages and rhythms characteristic of flamenco and other Spanish movements, but you can't call this music 100% flamenco).<ref name=\"peo\" /> He claims to have been \"infected\" with this traditional Spanish style of music and dance. \u201cI know the style I'm working in now,\u201d the musician says in one of his interviews, \u201cthis is the sound of a classic Spanish instrument with nylon strings and the sound of a tree that fascinates me\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rg.ru/2011/03/03/didula.html|title=\u0414\u0438\u0434\u044e\u043b\u044f: \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0437\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u0448\u0438\u0440\u043e\u043a \u0434\u0443\u0448\u043e\u0439|website=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430}}</ref> \"My pulse accelerated when I heard this Spanish music.\" This style is now my business card.\"<ref name=\"abc\" /> The first DiDuLa \"Flamenco\" album was released in 2000.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n== DiDuLa Group ==\nIn 2002, DiDuLa gathered a group of musicians and began touring in Russia<ref>{{cite web|title=The concert of Belarus guitarist Valery Didula was sold out in Penza|url=https://penzanews.ru/en/culture/50840-2011|website=penzanews.ru|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14|publication-date=}}.</ref> and the United States.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nDiDuLa Group consists of: percussionists (Michail Drumberg and Andrei Atabekov), keyboard  (Khaibula Magomedov), bass  (Philip Borodin) and Wind instruments\n\n(Valery Skladanny and Ramil Mulikov).<ref name=\"peo\"/>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n2000 - Flamenco (Audio CD)\n\n2002 - Road to Baghdad (Audio CD)\n\n2004 - Legend (Audio CD)\n\n2006 - Cave town of inkerman (Audio CD)\n\n2006 - Color Dreams (Audio CD)\n2007 - Music of an Unreleased Movie (Audio CD)\n\n2010 - Fragrance (Audio CD)\n2012 - Ornamental (Audio CD)\n\n2013 - Once Upon a Time (Audio CD + DVD)\n\n2017 - Aquamarine (Audio CD)\n\n2019 - The Seventh Sense (Audio CD)\n\n=== Live albums and videos ===\n\n2006 - Live in Moscow (Audio CD, DVD)\n\n2009 - Live in Saint Petersburg (DVD + 2CD)\n\n2009 - Dear Six Strings (film about the group, DVD)\n\n2013 - Live in Kremlin (2DVD + 3CD)\n\n=== Collections ===\n\n2006 - Grand Collection (Audio CD, MP3 CD)\n\n2003 - The Best (also known as Satin Coast) (Audio CD)\n\n2013 - DiDuLa. 100 best songs (MP3 CD)\n\n=== Production work ===\n\n2008 - Denis Asimovich \u201cHommage to Cheslav Drozdievich\u201d\n\n2012 - Igor Dedusenko \u201cPrayer\u201d\n\n=== Video clips ===\n\n* {{YouTube|title=DiDuLa - \"Cave town of Inkerman\"|id=YQuOq1BrFwQ}}\n* {{YouTube|title=DiDuLa - \"Arabica\"|id=n-Iew4uKpZ4}}\n* {{YouTube|title=DiDuLa - \"Isadora\"|id=96LVtBruvTs}}\n* {{YouTube|title=DiDuLa - \"Flamenco\"|id=96LVtBruvTs}}\n* {{YouTube|title=DiDuLa - Spain|id=Ho7j_PSnOvA}}\n* {{YouTube|title=DiDuLa - \"Leila\"|id=Ho7j_PSnOvA}}\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.didula.ru/ Official website DiDuLa]\n* [http://didula.ru/music/doc2.htm Discography]\n* [http://music.yandex.ru/#!/artist/41169/albums?hilite=artist-albums Album on Yandex music]\n* [https://itunes.apple.com/ru/artist/didula/id582811547 Album in Itunes]\n* [http://www.peoples.ru/art/music/guitars/didula/ DiDuLa on website People]\n* [http://www.abc-guitars.com/pages/didjulja.htm DiDuLa in the encyclopedia of guitarists]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080620045512/http://www.mkset.ru/news/culture/5989/ \u00ab\u0414\u0438\u0434\u044e\u043b\u044f \u0441\u043f\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0439\u043d\u043e \u0445\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442 \u0432 \u0431\u0443\u043b\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0443\u044e \u0441 \u0430\u0432\u043e\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0439\u00bb, \u0412\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0417\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430, \u041c\u041a\u0421, 17 \u043e\u043a\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044f 2006]\n* [http://guitar.ru/musicians/interview/didula.html Interview on guitar.ru]\n* [http://echo.msk.ru