t-align:center;\"|26\n| May 27, 2008\n| February 22, 2011\n|}\n\n==References==\n;General\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com/the-adventures-of-the-black-stallion/show/5000/episode.html |title=The Adventures of the Black Stallion Episode Guide |publisher=[[TV.com]] |accessdate=2006-02-22 }}\n\n;Specific\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0098754|title=The Adventures of The Black Stallion}}\n*{{tv.com show|the-adventures-of-the-black-stallion|The Adventures of The Black Stallion}}\n\n{{The Black Stallion}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adventures Of The Black Stallion, The}}\n[[Category:Television series about horses]]\n[[Category:1990s Canadian drama television series]]\n[[Category:1990 Canadian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1993 Canadian television series endings]]\n[[Category:Family Channel shows]]\n[[Category:1990 French television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1990 New Zealand television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1993 French television series endings]]\n[[Category:1993 New Zealand television series endings]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Adventures of the Black Stallion\n| image                = Adventures of the black stallion.jpg\n| caption              = Season 1 DVD cover\n| genre                = Adventure/Family\n| audio_format         = \n| runtime              = 30 minutes\n| creator              = \n| developer            = \n| producer             = [[Jonathan Hackett]]\n| executive_producer   = [[Tom Parkinson (filmmaker)|Tom Parkinson]]\n| starring             = [[Mickey Rooney]]<br />[[Richard Ian Cox]]\n| theme_music_composer = Terry Frewer\n| opentheme            = We Know the Wind\n| endtheme             = We Know the Wind (instrumental)\n| country              = Canada / France / New Zealand\n| location             = Canada / France / New Zealand\n| language             = [[English (language)|English]]\n| company              = [[Alliance Communications]]<br>Atlantique Productions\n| network              = [[The Family Channel (United States)|The Family Channel]]<br>[[YTV (TV channel)|YTV]]<br>[[M6 (TV channel)|M6]]\n| first_aired          = September 15, 1990\n| last_aired           = May 16, 1993\n| num_seasons          = 3\n| num_episodes         = 78\n| list_episodes        = \n| related              = [[The Black Stallion (film)|The Black Stallion]]<br /> [[The Black Stallion Returns]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Adventures of the Black Stallion''''' is a [[France|French]] New Zealand and [[Canada|Canadian]]-produced [[television series]] that starred [[Mickey Rooney]] and [[Richard Ian Cox]], as a trainer and a teenaged horse racer and was loosely based on the book series by [[Walter Farley]].<ref>Brooks, Tim & Marsh, Earle (2007).  ''The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows 1946-Present'' (9th ed.).  New York:  Ballantine Books.  {{ISBN|978-0-345-49773-4}}.</ref>  The series originally ran on [[The Family Channel (United States)|The Family Channel]] and [[YTV (TV channel)|YTV]] from September 15, 1990 to May 16, 1993, before cancellation. It has since been shown in re-runs throughout the world. Mickey Rooney is the only original cast member from ''[[The Black Stallion (film)|The Black Stallion]]'' to reprise his role in the show. In France, the show ran on [[M6 (TV channel)|M6]] from April 20, 1991.\n\nMost of the episodes are set around Canada.  During the second and third season, the show moves away from the farm, and has many episodes set in [[New Zealand]], [[Paris]] and the United States. ''The Adventures of The Black Stallion'' was filmed on location in British Columbia, Canada, as well as France and New Zealand. 16 horses portrayed The Black across the three countries<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://richardiancox.tumblr.com/post/172529257996/hi-was-docs-keepin-time-the-only-horse-excluding|title=Hi, was Docs Keepin Time the only horse (excluding stunts) that played The Black in the series? He looks different  to me in season 3.|work=Portrait of the Artist as Me|access-date=2018-04-03}}</ref>.\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe show follows the life of fifteen-year-old horse racer Alec Ramsay ([[Richard Ian Cox]]), his wild stallion The Black, and their trainer Henry Dailey ([[Mickey Rooney]]). In the series, Alec's father died before the series start, leaving Alec and his mother to run Hopeful Farm.  The show focuses both on life at Hopeful Farm and on the racing circuit.  During the first season, most of the races are unprofessional circuit races and [[match race]]s because The Black's an unpapered horse, meaning there is no proof of his lineage.  During the second season, The Black's history is uncovered and Alec is able to obtain his papers, allowing him to be raced on the professional circuits around the world.\n\nThe series maintained that Alec was the only one who can ride The Black.<ref>Terrace, Vincent  (2009).  ''Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2007'' (Volume 1).  Jefferson, North Carolina:  McFarland & Company, Inc. {{ISBN|978-0-7864-3305-6}}.</ref>  He is known for having a violent temper with anyone besides Alec, though he does allow some people around the farm to hold his halter and lead him around, most notably Henry. He only seems to do grudgingly, however, and tends to be far less tolerant of others if Alec isn't around to keep him under control. To help keep the high-strung horse calm at the track, the gelding Napoleon is frequently taken on the road with them.\n\n==Characters==\n*[[Mickey Rooney]] as Henry Dailey\n*[[Richard Ian Cox]] as Alec Ramsay\n*[[imdbname:0276810|Marian Filali]] as Nicole Berthier (Season 2 - Season 3)\n*[[Michele Goodger]] as Belle Ramsey (Season 1)\n*[[Virginie Demains]] as Catherine Varnier (Season 1)\n*[[Jean-Paul Solal]] as Pierre Chastel (Season 1)\n*[[David Taylor (actor)|David Taylor]] as Nathaniel 'Nate' MacKay (Season 3)\n*[[Docs Keepin Time]] as [[The Black Stallion|The Black]]\n\n==Reception==\nIn 1991, the series was nominated for a [[Young Artist Award]] in the \"Best Off-Prime Time or Cable Family Series\" category, and while it lost to ''[[Harry and the Hendersons (TV series) | Harry and the Hendersons]]'', Richard Ian Cox won the award for the \"Best Young Actor Starring in an Off-Prime Time or Cable Family Series\" category.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms13.htm |title=13th Annual Awards |publisher=[[Young Artist Award]]s |accessdate=2008-02-22 }}</ref> Cox was nominated again in 1992 for the \"Best Young Actor Starring in a Cable Series\" category.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms14.htm |title=14th Annual Awards |publisher=[[Young Artist Award]]s |accessdate=2008-02-22 }}</ref>  In the same year, [[Mickey Rooney]] was nominated for a [[Gemini Award]] in the category of \"Best Performance by an Actor in a Continuing Leading Dramatic Role\" for his portrayal of Henry Dailey.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://academy.ca/hist/history.cfm?categid=9503&shownum=6&winonly=0&awards=2&rtype=5&curstep=4 |title=Canadian Awards History Search:  6th Geminis \u2013 Best Performance by an Actor in a Continuing Leading Dramatic Role |publisher=Academy of Canadian Cinema & Television |accessdate=2008-02-22 }}</ref>\n\n==Episode list==\nWhen the show was first aired, many of the episodes were shown out of production order, especially during the first season.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Season !! Episodes !! Year !! Prod. line !! Region 1 Release Date\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#6c9; height:10px;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''[[#Season 1: 1990\u20131991|1]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 26\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1990\u20131991\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''1'''xx\n|December 5, 2006\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#69f; height:10px;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''[[#Season 2: 1991\u20131992|2]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 26\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1991\u20131992\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"