{"title_page": "Fiat RS.14", "text_new": "<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n |name=RS.14\n |image=Fiat RS.14.jpg\n |caption=\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Type\n |type=Long-range [[Maritime patrol aircraft|maritime reconnaissance]] floatplane\n |manufacturer=[[Fiat Aviazione|Fiat]]\n |designer=[[Manlio Stiavelli]]\n |first flight=May 1939\n |introduced=May 1941\n |retired=1948<ref>[http://www.aeroflight.co.uk/waf/italy/af/ital-af2-all-time.htm aeriflight]</ref>\n |status=\n |primary user= {{lang|it|[[Regia Aeronautica]]}}\n |more users=[[Italian Co-Belligerent Air Force]]\n |produced=May 1941 - September 1943\n |number built=186 (includes 2 prototypes) <ref>[http://www.alieuomini.it/catalogo/dettaglio_catalogo/cmasa_rs,24.html Fiat RS.14]</ref>\n |variants with their own articles=\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Fiat RS.14''' was an [[Italy|Italian]] long-range maritime strategic [[reconnaissance]] [[floatplane]]. The RS.14 was a four/five seat all-metal [[cantilever]] low/mid-wing [[monoplane]] powered by two wing-mounted 626&nbsp;kW (840&nbsp;hp) [[Fiat A.74 R.C.38]] engines. It had a conventional cantilever [[Empennage|tail unit]] with a single [[fin]] and rudder. Its [[Landing gear|undercarriage]] consisted of two large [[Float (nautical)|floats]] on [[strut]]s. It had a glazed nose for an observer or [[Bombardier (air force)|bomb aimer]]. The pilot and copilot sat side by side with a wireless operator's compartment behind them. In the [[Bomber|bombing]] role the RS.14 was fitted with a long ventral gondola to carry various combinations of [[Anti-submarine warfare|anti-submarine]] [[Aerial bomb|bombs]] (up to {{cvt|400|kg|lb|abbr=on}}).\n\n==Development==\nThe RS.14 was designed by [[Manlio Stiavelli]] at the [[CMASA]] works at [[Marina di Pisa]]. The first of two prototypes flew in May 1939.\n\nA prototype landplane version '''AS.14''' was built and first flown on 11 August 1943. It was designed as a [[ground-attack aircraft]] and intended to be armed with a {{cvt|37|mm|in|abbr=on}} [[Autocannon|cannon]] and {{cvt|12.7|mm|in|abbr=on}} [[machine gun]]s. It was not ordered and no others were built.\n\n==Operational history==\n\n[[File:Breda safat of fiat rs14.jpg|thumb|The waist gun positions of a FIAT RS.14]]\nThe RS.14 went into service with the Italian Air Force with a number of maritime strategic reconnaissance squadrons at bases around the Italian coast and also in [[Sicily]] and [[Sardinia]]. They were used for [[Convoy#Naval convoys|convoy]] escort duties and [[Anti-submarine warfare|anti-submarine]] patrols. Occasionally they engaged in aerial combat, obtaining unexpected victories such as when, on Saturday 9 May 1942, an RS.14 intercepted Spitfires that took off from the carriers [[HMS Eagle]] and [[USS Wasp]], headed for [[Malta]], and machine-gunned two. The two RAF fighters collided and fell into the sea. Both pilots were killed.<ref name=\"Rogers 2000, p. 149\">Rogers 2010, p. 149.</ref> After the [[Armistice between Italy and Allied armed forces|1943 Armistice]] a few survivors were operated by the Italian Co-Belligerent Air Force. At the end of the [[Second World War]] the aircraft were used for [[Liaison aircraft|liaison]] duties around the Mediterranean carrying up to four passengers.\n\n==Variants==\n;RS.14\n:Production floatplane with 626&nbsp;kW (840&nbsp;hp) [[Fiat A.74 R.C.38]] engines, 188 built including two [[prototype]]s.\n;AS.14\n:Landplane version with retractable landing gear, one built.\n\n==Operators==\n;{{flag|Kingdom of Italy}}\n* ''[[Regia Aeronautica]]''\n* [[Italian Co-Belligerent Air Force]]\n;{{ITA}}\n* [[Italian Air Force]] operated six surviving Fiat RS.14 until 1948<ref>[http://www.aeronautica.difesa.it/storia/1946_1950/Pagine/CON-UMILT%C3%80-RICONQUISTIAMO-IL-CIELO.aspx \"Birth of Aeronautica Militare\"] ''Aeronautica Militare''. Retrieved 13 July 2016</ref>\n\n==Specifications==\n{{Aerospecs\n|ref=Donald, 1997, pg 413.\n|met or eng?=met\n|crew=three\n|capacity=\n|length m=14.1\n|length ft=46\n|length in=3.25\n|span m=19.54\n|span ft=64\n|span in=1.25\n|height m=5.63\n|height ft=18\n|height in=5.75\n|wing area sqm=50\n|wing area sqft=538.21\n|empty weight kg=5,470\n|empty weight lb=12,059\n|gross weight kg=8,470\n|gross weight lb=18,673\n|eng1 number=2\n|eng1 type=[[Fiat A.74 R.C.38]] 14-cylinder [[Radial engine|radial piston]]\n|eng1 kw=626\n|eng1 hp=840\n|max speed kmh=390\n|max speed mph=242\n|cruise speed kmh=<!-- if max speed unknown -->\n|cruise speed mph=<!-- if max speed unknown -->\n|range km=2,500\n|range miles=1,553\n|endurance h=<!-- if range unknown -->\n|endurance min=<!-- if range unknown -->\n|ceiling m=6,300\n|ceiling ft=20,670\n|climb rate ms=\n|climb rate ftmin=\n|armament1=1 \u00d7 12.7 mm (0.5 in) machine gun\n|armament2=2 \u00d7 7.7 mm (0.303 in) machine guns\n|armament3=up to 400 kg (882 lb) of [[Aerial bomb|bombs]]\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Aircontent\n<!-- include as many lines are appropriate. additional lines/entries with carriage return. -->\n|related=<!-- related developments -->\n|similar aircraft=<!-- similar or comparable aircraft -->\n* [[Hall XPTBH]]\n* [[Heinkel He 115]]\n* [[Fokker T.VIII]]\n|lists=<!-- related lists -->\n* [[List of aircraft of World War II]]\n* [[List of Interwar military aircraft]]\n|see also=<!-- other relevant information -->\n* [[CANT Z.501]]\n* [[CANT Z.506]]\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Fiat RS.14}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |editor-last=Donald |editor-first=David |title=The Encyclopedia of World Aircraft |publisher=Prospero Books |year=1997 |isbn=1-85605-375-X}}\n* Mondey, David (1984), ''The Concise Guide to Axis Aircraft of World War II'', Chancellor Press, {{ISBN|1-85152-966-7}}\n* Rogers, Anthony, ''Battle over Malta - Aircraft Losses & Crash Sites 194042''. Phoenix Mill Thrupp - Strout, Gloucestershire, Sutton Publishing, 2000. {{ISBN|0-7509-2392-X}}.\n* The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Aircraft (Part Work 1982-1985), 1985, Orbis Publishing, Page 1812\n<!-- ==External links== -->\n\n{{Fiat aircraft}}\n\n[[Category:1940s Italian patrol aircraft]]\n[[Category:Floatplanes]]\n[[Category:Fiat aircraft|RS.14]]\n[[Category:Aircraft first flown in 1939]]\n[[Category:Mid-wing aircraft]]\n[[Category:Twin piston-engined tractor aircraft]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n |name=RS.14\n |image=Fiat RS.14.jpg\n |caption=\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Type\n |type=Long-range [[Maritime patrol aircraft|maritime reconnaissance]] floatplane\n |manufacturer=[[Fiat Aviazione|Fiat]]\n |designer=[[Manlio Stiavelli]]\n |first flight=May 1939\n |introduced=May 1941\n |retired=1948<ref>[http://www.aeroflight.co.uk/waf/italy/af/ital-af2-all-time.htm aeriflight]</ref>\n |status=\n |primary user=''[[Regia Aeronautica]]''\n |more users=[[Italian Co-Belligerent Air Force]]\n |produced=May 1941 - September 1943\n |number built=186 (includes 2 prototypes) <ref>[http://www.alieuomini.it/catalogo/dettaglio_catalogo/cmasa_rs,24.html Fiat RS.14]</ref>\n |variants with their own articles=\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Fiat RS.14''' was an [[Italy|Italian]] long-range maritime strategic [[reconnaissance]] [[floatplane]]. The RS.14 was a four/five seat all-metal [[cantilever]] low/mid-wing [[monoplane]] powered by two wing-mounted 626&nbsp;kW (840&nbsp;hp) [[Fiat A.74 R.C.38]] engines. It had a conventional cantilever [[Empennage|tail unit]] with a single [[fin]] and rudder. Its [[Landing gear|undercarriage]] consisted of two large [[Float (nautical)|floats]] on [[strut]]s. It had a glazed nose for an observer or [[Bombardier (air force)|bomb aimer]]. The pilot and copilot sat side by side with a wireless operator's compartment behind them. In the [[Bomber|bombing]] role the RS.14 was fitted with a long ventral gondola to carry various combinations of [[Anti-submarine warfare|anti-submarine]] [[Aerial bomb|bomb]]s (up to 400&nbsp;kg/882&nbsp;lb).\n\n==Development==\nThe RS.14 was designed by [[Manlio Stiavelli]] at the [[CMASA]] works at [[Marina di Pisa]]. The first of two prototypes flew in May 1939.\n\nA prototype landplane version '''AS.14''' was built and first flown on 11 August 1943. It was designed as a [[ground-attack aircraft]] and intended to be armed with a 37&nbsp;mm (1.46&nbsp;in) [[Autocannon|cannon]] and 12.7&nbsp;mm (0.5&nbsp;in) [[machine gun]]s. It was not ordered and no others were built.\n[[File:Breda safat of fiat rs14.jpg|thumb|right|The waist gun positions of a FIAT RS.14]]\n\n==Operational history==\nThe RS.14 went into service with the Italian Air Force with a number of maritime strategic reconnaissance squadrons at bases around the Italian coast and also in [[Sicily]] and [[Sardinia]]. They were used for [[Convoy#Naval convoys|convoy]] escort duties and [[Anti-submarine warfare|anti-submarine]] patrols. Occasionally they engaged in aerial combat, obtaining unexpected victories such as when, on Saturday 9 May 1942, an RS.14 intercepted Spitfires that took off from the carriers [[HMS Eagle]] and [[USS Wasp]], headed for [[Malta]], and machine-gunned two. The two RAF fighters collided and fell into the sea. Both pilots were killed.<ref name=\"Rogers 2000, p. 149\">Rogers 2010, p. 149.</ref>\nAfter the [[Armistice between Italy and Allied armed forces|1943 Armistice]] a few survivors were operated by the Italian Co-Belligerent Air Force. At the end of the [[World War II|war]] the aircraft were used for [[Liaison aircraft|liaison]] duties around the Mediterranean carrying up to four passengers.\n\n==Variants==\n;RS.14\n:Production floatplane with 626&nbsp;kW (840&nbsp;hp) [[Fiat A.74 R.C.38]] engines, 188 built including two [[prototype]]s.\n;AS.14\n:Landplane version with retractable landing gear, one built.\n\n==Operators==\n;{{flag|Kingdom of Italy}}\n*''[[Regia Aeronautica]]''\n*[[Italian Co-Belligerent Air Force]]\n;{{ITA}}\n*[[Italian Air Force]] operated six surviving Fiat RS.14 until 1948<ref>[http://www.aeronautica.difesa.it/storia/1946_1950/Pagine/CON-UMILT%C3%80-RICONQUISTIAMO-IL-CIELO.aspx \"Birth of Aeronautica Militare\"] ''Aeronautica Militare''. Retrieved 13 July 2016</ref>\n\n==Specifications==\n{{Aerospecs\n|ref=Donald, 1997, pg 413.\n|met or eng?=met\n|crew=three\n|capacity=\n|length m=14.1\n|length ft=46\n|length in=3.25\n|span m=19.54\n|span ft=64\n|span in=1.25\n|height m=5.63\n|height ft=18\n|height in=5.75\n|wing area sqm=50\n|wing area sqft=538.21\n|empty weight kg=5,470\n|empty weight lb=12,059\n|gross weight kg=8,470\n|gross weight lb=18,673\n|eng1 number=2\n|eng1 type=[[Fiat A.74 R.C.38]] 14-cylinder [[Radial engine|radial piston]]\n|eng1 kw=626\n|eng1 hp=840\n|max speed kmh=390\n|max speed mph=242\n|cruise speed kmh=<!-- if max speed unknown -->\n|cruise speed mph=<!-- if max speed unknown -->\n|range km=2,500\n|range miles=1,553\n|endurance h=<!-- if range unknown -->\n|endurance min=<!-- if range unknown -->\n|ceiling m=6,300\n|ceiling ft=20,670\n|climb rate ms=\n|climb rate ftmin=\n|armament1=1 \u00d7 12.7 mm (0.5 in) machine gun\n|armament2=2 \u00d7 7.7 mm (0.303 in) machine guns\n|armament3=up to 400 kg (882 lb) of [[Aerial bomb|bomb]]s\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Aircontent\n<!-- include as many lines are appropriate. additional lines/entries with carriage return. -->\n|related=<!-- related developments -->\n|similar aircraft=<!-- similar or comparable aircraft -->\n*[[Hall XPTBH]]\n*[[Heinkel He 115]]\n*[[Fokker T.VIII]]\n|lists=<!-- related lists -->\n*[[List of aircraft of World War II]]\n*[[List of Interwar military aircraft]]\n|see also=<!-- other relevant information -->\n*[[CANT Z.501]]\n*[[CANT Z.506]]\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Fiat RS.14}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |editor-last=Donald |editor-first=