{"title_page": "J. G. Hertzler", "text_new": "{{Short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = J. G. Hertzler\n| image =Hertzler Campaign Headshot.jpg\n| caption = John G. Hertzler (2011)\n| birth_name = John Garman Hertzler Jr.\n| birth_date =  {{birth date and age|1950|3|18}}<!-- confirmed by Hertzler on talk page -->\n| birth_place = [[Savannah, Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_date =\n| residence = [[Trumansburg, New York]], U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ithaca.com/news/citizen-twain-performance-art-politics/article_74036584-511e-11e7-95af-fb9055287b29.html|title=Citizen Twain: Performance Art Politics|first=Warren|last=Greenwood|date=|website=ithaca.com|accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n| other_names = John Noah Hertzler <!-- stage name for the 1980s productions -->\n| alma_mater ={{Plainlist|\n* [[Bucknell University]]\n* [[University of Maryland]]\n* [[American University]]\n}}\n| occupation = Actor, author, screenwriter, activist\n| years_active = 1978\u2013present\n| party = \n| children = 1<ref name=\"bio\"/><ref name=\"1701 interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1701st.com/interview-with-j-g-hertzler/|title=Interview with J.G. Hertzler|interviewer=Phil Cherry|date=April 14, 2015|work=The 1701st Fleet|accessdate=June 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401084317/http://www.1701st.com/interview-with-j-g-hertzler/|archive-date=April 1, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"little review 2000\"/>\n}}\n\n'''John Garman Hertzler Jr.''' (born March 18, 1950)<!-- DOB confirmed, see talk page --><ref name=\"mother\">{{cite web|url=http://portroyal200.com/view.php?id=1155|title=Port Royal People :: Eleanor Frances (BEAVER) HERTZLER|author=|date=|work=portroyal200.com|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"the circuit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecircuitfilm.com/#!jg-hertzler/zr7db|title=The Circuit Film|author=|date=|work=thecircuitfilm.com|accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"usa today\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/11/08/klingon-warrior-ny-town-board/3479463/|title=Klingon warrior elected to N.Y. town board|first=Joseph |last=Spector|date=November 8, 2013|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref> is an American [[actor]], author, screenwriter, and activist best known for his role on ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'' as the [[Klingon]] [[General officer|General]] (and later [[Chancellor]]) [[Martok]], whom he portrayed from 1995 until the series' end in 1999.\n\nHertzler began his acting career in the 1970s, doing mostly stage acting and appearing in some films. He guest starred in a few episodes for different television shows before landing the part of Alcalde Ignacio De Soto in the early 1990s show ''[[Zorro (1990 TV series)|Zorro]]''. In addition to ''Deep Space Nine'', Hertzler has appeared on several other ''[[Star Trek]]'' shows, written two ''Star Trek'' novels, and has made appearances at ''Star Trek'' and science fiction conventions. Hertzler lives in the [[Finger Lakes]] region of New York where he was a lecturer at Cornell's theater department, and has been active in the area's regional politics, as well as writing a screenplay.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and education===\nHertzler was born in [[Savannah, Georgia]]. His parents were from [[Port Royal, Pennsylvania]],<ref name=\"bio\"/><ref name=\"mother\"/> and his family is descended from German-speaking Amish families.<ref name=\"little review 2000\"/>  His father John G. Hertzler served in the U.S. Air Force,<ref name=\"mother\"/><ref name=\"popmythology\">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmythology.com/j-g-hertzler-star-trek-axanar-interview/|title=Interview: J.G. Hertzler on 'Star Trek: Axanar,' Martok and William Shatner | work= Pop Mythology |date=August 20, 2015|accessdate=June 24, 2016}}</ref> and his mother Eleanor Frances Beaver Hertzler was a Latin and French teacher.<ref name=\"mother\"/><ref name=\"trektoday\">{{cite web|url=http://www.trektoday.com/articles/weekend_at_holodiction_2.shtml|title=The Trek Nation \u2013 A Weekend At Holodiction \u2013 Part 2|author=|date=|work=trektoday.com|accessdate=June 24, 2016}}</ref> His family lived in cities around the world including: [[St. Joe, Missouri]]; [[El Paso, Texas]]; and [[Casablanca]] in [[Morocco]].<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=https://dems4ulysses.wordpress.com/john-hertzler/|title=Town Board\u2013 John Hertzler|last=Hertzler|first=John|date=September 23, 2013|work=Democrats 4 Ulysses (Ulysses Democratic Committee)|via=Wordpress|accessdate=June 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016175728/https://dems4ulysses.wordpress.com/john-hertzler/|archive-date=October 16, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"little review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.littlereview.com/getcritical/trektalk/hertzler.htm|title=J.G. Hertzler, Intergalactic Tough Guy \u2013 General Martok goes on a rampage|first=Michelle Erica | last=Green | year=1999 | work=Little Review | accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref><!--  and his mother was a French and Latin high school teacher. --> He grew up mostly in the Washington, D.C. area, and attended [[Bucknell University]], playing linebacker on their football squad.<ref name=\"usa today\"/><ref name=\"little review\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bucknellbison.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=32100&ATCLID=210250205 | title=2015 Bucknell Football Media Guide | year=2015 | page=101 | work=[[Bucknell Bison|Bucknell University Athletics]] }}</ref> While there, he got into acting when the drama department recruited him for a production of ''[[Marat/Sade]]'' as they were looking for a big guy for one of the roles.<ref name=\"latimes 1993\"/> After graduating in political science in 1972,<ref name=\"bucknell alumni\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bucknell.edu/interested-in-bucknell/who-we-are/bucknell-stories/alumni-stories/john-hertzler-72.html|title=Alumni Profiles \u2013 John Hertzler '72|author=|date=May 2014|work=[[Bucknell University]]|accessdate=June 24, 2016}}</ref> he got his master's in set design at the [[University of Maryland]],<ref name=\"little review 2000\"/><ref name=\"little review\"/> and attended law school for a year at [[American University]].<!-- see talk page --> While he was in the DC area, he worked in the federal government,<ref name=\"bio\"/><ref name=\"facebook\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/john.g.hertzler|title=John G. Hertzler \u2013 Facebook|author=|date=|work=facebook.com|accessdate=June 24, 2016}}</ref> including with the Nixon Administration for the National Environmental Policy Act,<ref name=\"little review\"/> and took an assortment of jobs to practice theatre including waiting at a dinner theater, bartending, and taxi-driving.<ref name=\"little review\"/>\n\n===Acting career===\n<!-- expand on early film and television career -->\nHertzler worked in the Washington area on theatre projects. On the movie screen, he portrayed Lucas in the horror film ''[[The Redeemer: Son of Satan]]'' (also known as ''Class Reunion Massacre''), which was released in 1978.<ref name=\"redeemer\"/><ref name=\"redeemer2\"/> Hertzler also had a role in the feature film ''[[...And Justice for All (film)|And Justice for All]]'' which starred [[Al Pacino]], released in 1979.<ref name=\"little review\"/> He also worked in New York City on the Broadway production ''[[The Bacchae]]'' as King Pentheus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/production/the-bacchae-circle-in-the-square-theatre-vault-0000003276|title=The Bacchae @ Circle in the Square Theatre | work=[[Playbill]] | accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | newspaper=[[Asbury Park Press]] | location=New Jersey | date=October 3, 1980 | page=32 | title=The Bacchae proves important stage event | accessdate=July 17, 2016 | url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/147673125/ |url-access=subscription  }}</ref><!-- this article was circulated to various newspapers nationally with different titles, see also https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/19946555/, subscription required to view in detail --><ref name=\"new york\">{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IuQCAAAAMBAJ|title=Revels without a cause | journal=[[New York Magazine]] | publisher=New York Media, LLC| first=John | last=Simon | date=October 20, 1990 | page=101 | accessdate=July 17, 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref> In 1981,<!-- year confirmed by Hertzler on talk page --> he moved to San Francisco to join the [[American Conservatory Theater]] (ACT) where he acted and directed in a number of productions including ''[[The Admirable Crichton]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.worldcat.org/archivegrid/collection/data/84120141|title=ArchiveGrid : The admirable Crichton [videorecording] / American Conservatory Theatre presents ; [written] by James M. Barrie ; directed by Michael Winters.|author=|date=|work=worldcat.org|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Richard II (play)|Richard II]]'',<ref name=\"latimes 1993\"/> ''[[Dial M for Murder]]'',<ref name=\"stanford dialm\">{{cite news | url=http://stanforddailyarchive.com/cgi-bin/stanford?a=d&d=stanford19831207-01.2.79&e=-------en-20--1--txt-txIN------- | title=ACT murders Dial M | first=Melinda | last=Israel | newspaper=[[The Stanford Daily]] | volume=184 | issue=49 | date=December 7, 1983 }}</ref> and a number of Shakespeare productions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149475085/|title=Annual Shakespeare under the stars festival tickets available | page=78 | newspaper=[[Reno Gazette-Journal]] | date=August 8, 1985 | via=newspapers.com|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://he.palgrave.com/resources/sample-chapters/9780230546776_sample.pdf | title=A Directory of Shakespeare in Performance 1970\u20131990 | volume=Vol. 2: USA and Canada | first1=John | last1=O'Connor | first2=K. | last2=Goodland | publisher= Palgrave Macmillan | year=2010 | isbn= 978-0-230-54677-6 }}</ref> He was an instructor with ACT,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inlandarts.com/profile/detail/265|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818115802/http://www.inlandarts.com/profile/detail/265|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 18, 2016|title=Artist Detail \u2013 Chuck Abernathy|author=|date=|work=Inland Arts|access-date=July 17, 2016|quote=He's studied acting, improvisation, and stage combat in special workshops with American Conservatory Theatre instructors Sydney Walker, Janice Hutchins, J. G. Hertzler, and J. Steven White.}}</ref> and had also worked with other theater productions such as ''[[Medea (play)|Medea]]'' with the [[Cincinnati Playhouse]].<ref name=\"latimes 1993\"/><ref>{{ cite news | url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/103705030/ | newspaper=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]] | title='Medea' eloquent, but lacking fire | page=76 |url-access=subscription  | date=February 23, 1983 | via=Newspapers.com }}</ref> He moved to Southern California in 1988 <!-- year confirmed by Hertzler on talk page --> and continued theatre work there.<ref name=\"latimes 1993\"/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xjn-M_plml8C&pg=PA535|title=The Best Plays of 1989\u20131990: The Complete Broadway and Off-Broadway Sourcebook|first1=Otis L.|last1=Guernsey|first2=Jeffrey|last2=Sweet|date=April 1, 2000|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|accessdate=July 17, 2016|via=Google Books|isbn=9781557830906}}</ref>\n\n<!-- TV roles, zorro -->\nHis first notable guest role on television was in 1990 on the ''[[Quantum Leap (TV series)|Quantum Leap]]'' episode \"The Sea Bride \u2013 June 3, 1954\".<ref name=\"wormhole riders\"/>  His first major television role was in the 1990s series ''[[Zorro (1990 TV series)|Zorro]]'' as Alcalde Ignacio De Soto, the antagonist character who replaces Ramone as the Alcalde (Mayor) of Los Angeles in the third and fourth seasons.<ref name=\"little review\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newworldzorro.com/analysis/alcaldedesoto.html|title=Alcalde Ignacio De Soto|first=Jennifer | last=White|date=|work=New World Zorro|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newworldzorro.com/presskitinfo/johnhertzler.html|title=John Hertzler's Biography|first=Jennifer|last=White|date=|work=New World Zorro|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref> The show was filmed in a studio lot outside of Madrid, Spain,<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.newworldzorro.com/presskitinfo/prodnotes.html|title=Zorro: The Series \u2013 Production Notes | via=Jennifer White (New World Zorro)|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref> and was broadcast on [[The Family Channel (American TV network, founded 1980)|The Family Channel]].<ref name=\"latimes 1993\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-08-20/entertainment/ca-25722_1_julius-caesar|title=Theater / Jan Herman: Actor Plays Heavies, Heroes With Equal Ease|first=Jan|last=Herman|date=August 20, 1993|accessdate=July 17, 2016|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> He was also involved in a television movie called ''Treasure Island: The Adventure Begins'' where he played a pirate called Black Dog. ''Treasure Island'' was broadcast to go along with a promotion for the [[Treasure Island Resort & Casino|casino resort in Las Vegas]].<ref name=\"popmythology\"/>\n\n[[file:Riverside Trek Fest 2014 (14349292930).jpg|thumb|left|Hertzler (standing) as [[Martok]], with [[Robert O'Reilly]] as [[Gowron]], at the Riverside Trek Fest in 2014]]\n<!-- how he got involved in star trek -->\nHertzler's first involvement in ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'' was in the series' [[television pilot|pilot]] episode \"[[Emissary (Star Trek: Deep Space Nine)|Emissary]]\" as the [[Vulcan (Star Trek)|Vulcan]] [[Starfleet ranks and insignia#Captain|captain]] of the Federation starship ''Saratoga''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tor.com/2013/04/23/star-trek-deep-space-nine-qemissaryq/|title=Star Trek: Deep Space Nine Rewatch: \"Emissary\"|author=|date=April 23, 2013|work=tor.com|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref> In an interview with Startrek.com, Hertzler said he had worked with [[Patrick Stewart]] at the [[Paramount Studios]] lot where Stewart ran some Shakespeare workshops. He would later audition for ''DS9'' multiple times, but did not receive any roles.<ref name=\"startrek interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.startrek.com/article/general-martok-from-ds9-j-g-hertzler|title=General Martok from DS9 \u2013 J.G. Hertzler|author=|date=|work=startrek.com|accessdate=June 24, 2016}}</ref> He was at the Paramount Studios auditioning for another series when ''DS9'' casting director Ron Surma had him read for Klingon General [[Martok]]. At first, Hertzler portrayed Martok as a mild-mannered Klingon, but when he was asked to make him angrier, he picked up a chair and threw it into a wall. The chair's leg stuck briefly and he said he had also inadvertently ripped his thumbnail causing it to bleed, but it had impressed the auditors and he landed the part.<ref name=\"little review\"/><ref name=\"startrek interview\"/>\n\nMartok debuted in the season 4 premiere  \"[[The Way of the Warrior (Star Trek: Deep Space Nine)|The Way of the Warrior]]\" followed by the season 5 premiere \"[[Apocalypse Rising]]\". His character was originally a [[Changelings (Star Trek)|changeling]] (shapeshifter) Dominion impostor. Hertzler said the writers chose Martok to be the changeling, because they thought that making the Klingon Chancellor [[Gowron]] to be a clone was \"too pat or too easy.\" After the Martok changeling was killed in the episode Apocalypse Rising, the writers then brought in the real Martok as a recurring character starting in season 5, during which he portrayed a one-eyed Klingon. He would play Martok for three seasons including the finale, by which time he had replaced Gowron as the leader of the Klingon Empire.<ref name=\"startrek interview\"/> Hertzler describes the part as an actor's dream because of its physicality and range. The character has been involved in many aspects of ''Deep Space Nine'' including frequently interacting with [[Worf (Star Trek)|Worf]].<ref name=\"little review 2000\"/><ref name=\"little review\"/>\n\n<!--- other DS9 roles-->\nHertzler played other characters in ''DS9'', including a changeling named Laas, in the episode \"[[Chimera (Star Trek: Deep Space Nine)|Chimera]]\", who interacts with main character [[Odo (Star Trek)|Odo]]. In an interview with Little Review, Hertzler said that he was concerned he would be recognized as Martok despite the makeup and character change, but it worked out okay. Credited as Garman Hertzler for the episode, he said that he got a chance to interact with some of the lead characters that Martok would not encounter, especially the ones played by [[Nana Visitor]] and [[Ren\u00e9 Auberjonois]].<ref name=\"little review 2000\"/> In portraying Laas, Hertzler said he tried to act like [[William Shatner]], but with a higher pitch.  Another guest character he did was Roy Ritterhouse, a painter/sketcher in the season 6 episode \"[[Far Beyond the Stars]]\".<ref name=\"startrek interview\"/>\n\nFollowing the end of ''DS9'', Hertzler played a [[Hirogen]] in the ''[[Star Trek: Voyager]]'' episode \"[[Tsunkatse (Star Trek: Voyager)|Tsunkatse]]\", which was noted for featuring pro wrestler [[Dwayne Johnson|Dwayne \"The Rock\" Johnson]]. In the episode, he and The Rock are conscripted alien fighters. Hertzler said that he also got to wrestle actress [[Jeri Ryan]] who played [[Seven of Nine]].<ref name=\"little review 2000\">{{cite web|url=http://www.littlereview.com/getcritical/trektalk/hertz2.htm|title=J.G. Hertzler Vs. The Rock|first=Michelle Erica | last=Green | year=2000| work=Little Review|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref> In ''[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]'', he played a Klingon lawyer in the episode \"[[Judgment (Star Trek: Enterprise)|Judgment]]\" and a  Klingon Captain in the episode \"[[Borderland (Star Trek: Enterprise)|Borderland]]\".  He made appearances at ''Star Trek'' and science fiction conventions and events.<ref name=\"startrek interview\"/> In 2015, Hertzler joined the cast on the fan-funded short film ''[[Star Trek: Axanar]]'' as Captain Samuel Travis of the Federation.<ref name=\"popmythology\"/><ref name=\"axanar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.axanarproductions.com/jg-hertzler-on-prelude-to-axanar/|title=JG Hertzler on \"Prelude to Axanar\"|author=|date=July 29, 2014|work=axanarproductions.com|accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"1701news\">{{cite web|url=http://1701news.com/node/916/jg-hertzler-captivated-axanar.html|title=J.G. Hertzler Captivated By 'Axanar' \u2013 1701News|author=|date=|work=1701news.com|accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"techtimes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/74911/20150808/interview-richard-hatch-discusses-star-trek-axanar-and-what-its-like-being-a-klingon.htm|title=Interview: Richard Hatch Discusses 'Star Trek: Axanar' And What It's Like Being A Klingon|date=August 8, 2015|first=Robin | last=Burks | work=Tech Times|accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOutside of the ''Star Trek'' world, Hertzler appeared in the television film ''[[Pirates of Silicon Valley]]'' where he portrayed director [[Ridley Scott]].<ref name=\"pirates variety\"/> He made guest appearances on ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'', ''[[Roswell (TV series)|Roswell]]'', ''[[Charmed]]'',  and ''[[Highlander: The Series]]''.\n\nIn 1995\u201396, he was involved in a national tour for the stage theatre production of ''[[Dial M for Murder]]'', in which he portrayed Max Halliday,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xmoppet.org/play/dialM.html|title=Roddy McDowall in the play, \"Dial 'M' for Murder\"|author=|date=|work=[[Roddy McDowall#External links|RM Tribute site (xmoppet.org)]]|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref> an American writer who gets involved in a love triangle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-10-26/features/1995299013_1_frederick-knott-lyric-opera-house-paces|title='Dial' has many wrong numbers Theater review: In a too-large setting at the Lyric Opera House, Frederick Knott's tight, little suspense drama|date=October 26, 1995|first=J. Wynn |last=Rousuck|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|accessdate=July 16, 2016|quote=Though Allen projects an attractive, girlish, ladylike quality, Hertzler comes across as bland, and James merely seems interested in getting through the play's deliberately convoluted paces \u2013 we never really sense a conniving mind at work.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/1996-02-22/entertainment/25655521_1_darling-inspector-hubbard-tony-wendice|title=Seems The Thrill Of This Thriller Is Sadly Gone|first=Clifford A. |last=Ridley|date=February 22, 1996 | newspaper=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]] | accessdate=July 17, 2016|quote=John James, whom many people appeared to recognize from the daytime serials, is quite good, too, as the dastardly Tony, and J.G. Hertzler and Michael Halsey do nicely as the writer and the hit person. }}</ref><!-- John James, whom many people appeared to recognize from the daytime serials, is quite good, too, as the dastardly Tony, and J.G. Hertzler and Michael Halsey do nicely as the writer and the hit person. --><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/1995-11-09/news/9511090017_1_community-theater-production-grace-kelly-film|title=Dial m Needs A Shot Of Energy|first=Frank | last=Rizzo | date=November 9, 1995|newspaper=[[The Hartford Courant]] | quote=J.G. Hertzler as the wife's former suitor gives a braying, ham- fisted performance. | accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<!-- video games -->\nHertzler has been involved in voice-over for video games and audio productions. Outside some ''Star Trek'' titles, he did the voice-over for the intro sequence of [[The 3DO Company|3DO]]'s ''[[Might and Magic IX]]'', and was the voice of [[Characters of the BioShock series#Dr. Grossman|Dr. Grossman]] in ''[[BioShock]]''<ref name=\"wormhole riders\"/><ref name=\"startrek interview\"/> and  [[Deathstroke]] and [[Ares (DC Comics)|Ares]] in ''[[Injustice: Gods Among Us]]''. Hertzler narrated the audio book entitled ''Barsk: The Elephants' Graveyard'', written by Star Trek linguist [[Lawrence M. Schoen|Lawrence Schoen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/entertainment/books/article57685138.html|title=Klingon language expert visits Triangle with new sci-fi novel|first=Corbie | last=Hill|date=February 1, 2016|newspaper=[[The News & Observer]] |accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===New York theater and teaching===\n<!-- List New York activities here -->\nDuring the 2005\u20132006 season, Hertzler played the role of Henry Drummond in productions of ''[[Inherit the Wind (play)|Inherit the Wind]]'' at [[Geva Theatre Center]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gevatheatre.org/plays/archive.php |title=Plays :: Past Season Archive |publisher=Geva Theatre |date= |access-date=December 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601044254/http://www.gevatheatre.org/plays/archive.php |archive-date=June 1, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and [[Cornell University|Cornell University's]] Schwartz Center for the Performing Arts.<ref name=\"usa today\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lansingstar.com/entertainment-archive/2310-inherit-the-wind-opens-at-schwartz-center|title=Inherit the Wind Opens at Schwartz Center \u2013 The Lansing Star Online|first=Leslie|last=Morris|date=|work=lansingstar.com|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Hertzler moved to [[Ulysses, New York]], and became a Resident Professional Teaching Associate (RPTA) in the [[Cornell University]] Department of Theatre, Film & Dance, where he has directed or performed in a number of productions through the 2010 season.<ref name=\"usa today\"/><ref name=\"bucknell alumni\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://theatrefilmdance.cornell.edu/schwartz-center/2009-10-productions.cfm |title=List of Schwartz Center productions for 2009\u201310 |publisher=Theatrefilmdance.cornell.edu |date=April 3, 2012 |accessdate=December 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.klingon.org/smboard/index.php?topic=1273.0 | title=Former Klingon helps young Cornellians prosper | first=Topher | last=Sanders | newspaper=[[Ithaca Journal]] | date=October 30, 2007 | accessdate=July 17, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822111531/http://www.klingon.org/smboard/index.php?topic=1273.0 | archive-date=August 22, 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2009, Hertzler directed an outdoor production of ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'' for the Ithaca Shakespeare Company at the [[F.R. Newman Arboretum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ithacashakespeare.org/prod/200907/index.php |title=A Midsummer Night's Dream (2009) : The Ithaca Shakespeare Company |publisher=Ithacashakespeare.org |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ithacashakespeare.org/about/history.php|title=Our History : The Ithaca Shakespeare Company|author=|date=|work=ithacashakespeare.org|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref> He also portrayed Lord Capulet in Cornell's production of ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'', which involved students as well as professional actors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cornell.edu/video/romeo-and-juliet-at-the-schwartz-center|title=Romeo and Juliet at the Schwartz Center \u2013 CornellCast|author=|date=|work=cornell.edu|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter Cornell, Hertzler has continued to do acting and teaching in the New York area, including hosting a workshop about Shakespeare acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://encoreplayers.org/shakespeak-acting-shakespeare-with-truth-grace/|title=Shakespeak: Acting Shakespeare with Truth & Grace|author=|date=April 22, 2015|work=encoreplayers.org|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nHertzler co-authored with novelist Jeffrey Lang two ''Star Trek'' novels, ''Left Hand of Destiny, Book 1'', and ''Left Hand of Destiny, Book 2''.<ref name=\"startrek interview\" /> which were published by Simon & Schuster.<ref name=\"little review 2000\"/> The novels follow Martok's and Worf's adventures following ''Deep Space Nine'' as they return to Q'onoS, with much of the focus on Martok's life.<ref name=\"little review 2000\"/><ref>{{cite web | first1=Charlie Jane | last1=Anders | url=http://io9.gizmodo.com/10-actors-who-kept-their-characters-alive-in-books-afte-1607273481 | title=10 Actors Who Kept Their Characters Alive In Books After Cancellation | publisher=[[Gizmodo]] | work=[[io9]] | date=July 18, 2014 | accessdate=July 17, 2016 | last2=Monson-Rosen | first2=Madeleine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.trektoday.com/reviews/books/the_left_hand_of_destiny.shtml | title=The Trek Nation \u2013 The Left Hand Of Destiny | work=Trek Today | date=May 4, 2003 | accessdate=July 17, 2016 | last=Bundy | first=Jacqueline}}</ref>\n\nHertzler has also written an original screenplay, ''Dancing with Sancho Panza'', inspired by his time in Spain when he worked on ''Zorro''.<!-- talk page, secondary ref to come -->  In June 2016, the announcement was made that the screenplay will be directed by [[Luis Mandoki]] with an anticipated release date of November 2017.<ref name=\"spyhollywood\">{{cite web | url=http://spyhollywood.com/film-dancing-with-sancho-panza-greenlighted/ | title=Film \"Dancing with Sancho Plaza\" Greenlighted | work=Spy Hollywood | date=April 29, 2016 | accessdate=June 24, 2016 | last=Ceffer | first=Lou}}</ref>\n\n===Political life and activism===\n[[File:HERTZLER CROMWELL ARRESTED.jpg|thumb|right|Hertzler and actor [[James Cromwell]] show their arrest citations at the Crestwood station protest]]\n\nIn 2013, Hertzler ran for a position on the [[Ulysses, New York|Ulysses]] town council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dems4ulysses.wordpress.com/john-hertzler/|title=Town Board\u2013 John Hertzler|work=Elect the Democratic Team for Ulysses!|via=Wordpress.com|access-date=October 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016175728/https://dems4ulysses.wordpress.com/john-hertzler/|archive-date=October 16, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> His involvement in politics was partly because of the issue of [[hydraulic fracturing]] and concerns that the method of drilling for natural gas would destroy the Finger Lakes region.<ref name=\"usa today\"/><ref name=\"bucknell alumni\"/> He also wanted the region's schools to get more state aid.<ref name=\"usa today\"/> He was elected and served on the board for a two-year term.<ref name=\"usa today\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ithaca.com/news/unofficial-election-results-in-tompkins-south-seneca-and-tioga-counties/article_f343ac50-432b-11e3-9ba2-001a4bcf887a.html|title=2013 Unofficial Election Results in Tompkins, South Seneca, Chemung and Tioga counties|date=November 6, 2013|<!-- author=staff reports-->|work=Ithaca Times}}</ref> In 2016, he was elected to the town council board for a four-year term extending to 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ulysses.ny.us/council/boards-town/|title=Members|author=|date=June 19, 2016|work=ulysses.ny.us|accessdate=June 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 election]], Hertzler endorsed Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] for President.<ref>{{cite tweet |author = J.G. Hertzler |date = July 2, 2015 |title = berniesanders.com/10000-at-madison-coliseum via @BernieSanders  I hope the Hillary supporters and Bernie detractors notice this!  Arriba America, Viva Bernie! |user = kethaman1 |number = 616618560752848898 |accessdate = March 9, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nHertzler and fellow ''[[Star Trek]]'' actor [[James Cromwell]] were among nineteen people arrested for disorderly conduct during a protest outside a Crestwood Midstream compressor station in [[Watkins Glen, New York]], on June 6, 2016. They were involved in the \"We Are Seneca Lake\" civil disobedience campaign against the [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]] green-lighting underground gas storage in [[Seneca Lake (New York)|Seneca Lake]]'s salt caverns, despite public opposition.<ref>[http://ecowatch.com/2016/06/06/star-trek-actors-arrested/ Star Trek Actors Arrested, Call on Gov. Cuomo to Boldly Go Beyond Fossil Fuels] \u2013 ''EcoWatch''</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ithacajournal.com/story/news/local/2016/06/06/star-trek-actors-among-19-arrested-seneca-lake-protest/85495036/ | title='Star Trek' actors among 19 arrested at Seneca Lake protest | date=June 6, 2016 | newspaper=[[Ithaca Journal]] | first=Lois | last=Wilson }}</ref>\n\nOn June 8, 2017, Hertzler announced his candidacy as a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House Representative]] for [[New York's 23rd congressional district]] in the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]]. As part of his campaign appearances, he plans to act \"in the persona of [[Mark Twain]]\", to present his ideas \"through the brilliant humorist for all ages\".  He stated that this was a tribute both to Twain, who resided once in [[Elmira, New York|Elmira]], and to actor [[Hal Holbrook]], who had portrayed Twain on stage for more than six decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.14850.com/06104035-hertzler-ny23-reed/|title=\"Star Trek\" actor will challenge Tom Reed for New York 23rd - 14850|date=June 10, 2017 |first=Mark H. |last=Anbinder|website=14850.com|location=Ithaca, New York|accessdate=June 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ithacajournal.com/story/news/2017/06/12/klingon-run-mark-twain-against-rep-reed/389053001/|title='Klingon' to run as 'Mark Twain' against Rep. Reed|first=Matt |last=Steecker|date=June 12, 2017|work=Ithaca Journal|accessdate=June 13, 2017}}</ref> On September 25, 2017 Hertzler announced his decision to leave the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] and run as an independent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://whcuradio.com/morning-newswatch/hertzler-leaves-democratic-party/|title=Hertzler leaves Democratic Party|last=Rayburn|first=Lee|date=September 25, 2017|work=WHCU|access-date=September 28, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929044513/https://whcuradio.com/morning-newswatch/hertzler-leaves-democratic-party/|archive-date=September 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He advanced in the primary in June 2018, but later withdrew his candidacy prior to November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/John_Hertzler|title=John Hertzler - Ballotpedia|author=|date=|website=ballotpedia.org|accessdate=December 3, 2018}}</ref>\n<!--- Do not add personal life section per talk page -->\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ List of acting performances in television\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Source\n|-\n| {{dts|1990|05|02|format=y}} || ''[[Quantum Leap]]'' || Weathers Farrington || Ep. \"Sea Bride \u2013 June 3, 1954\" || <ref name=\"wormhole riders\">{{cite web|url=http://wormholeriders.com/blog/?p=31058|title=J.G. Hertzler: Shakespearean Klingon with Attitude!|first=Patricia|last=Stewart-Bertrand|date=February 20, 2013|work=Wormhole Riders|accessdate=June 24, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"startrek interview\"/><ref name=\"spyhollywood\"/><!-- also has audio interview --><ref name=\"starwrecked filmography\"/>\n|-\n| {{dts|1991}}\u201393 || ''[[Zorro (1990 TV series)|Zorro]]'' || Alcalde Ignacio de Soto || || <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.justpressplay.net/reviews/7374-zorro-the-complete-series.html|title=Zorro: The Complete Series|last=Osterweil|first=Willie|website=www.justpressplay.net|access-date=June 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvacres.com/west_new_zorro.htm|archive-url=https://archive.is/20160821024035/http://www.tvacres.com/west_new_zorro.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 21, 2016|title=TV ACRES: Westerns > The New Zorro (starring Duncan Regehr as Don Diego de la Vega)|website=www.tvacres.com|access-date=June 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"american western book\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aevGBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA456 | title=The American Western: A Complete Film Guide | first=Terry |last=Rowan | isbn= 9781300418580  | year=2013 | publisher=Lulu.com | page=456 }}</ref>{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=December 2017}}\n|-\n| {{dts|1992|12|19|format=y}} || ''[[Highlander (TV series)|Highlander]]'' || Marcus Korolus || Ep \"See No Evil\" || <ref name=\"spyhollywood\"/><ref name=\"starwrecked filmography\"/>\n|-\n| {{dts|1993}}\u201399 || ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'' || [[Martok]], others || Also Vulcan Captain in \"[[Emissary (Star Trek: Deep Space Nine)|Emissary]]\" || <ref name=\"little review 2000\"/><ref name=\"little review\"/><ref name=dayinthelife>{{cite journal|title=A Day in the Life... J.G. Hertzler|journal=Star Trek Explorer|date=2011|volume=3|issue=1|page=18}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1994|01|07|format=y}} || ''[[The Adventures of Brisco County, Jr.]]'' || Edward Hayes / Myron Stempler || Ep. \"Bounty Hunters Convention\" || <ref name=\"spyhollywood\"/><ref name=\"starwrecked filmography\"/>\n|-\n| {{dts|1994|11|05|format=y}} || ''[[Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman]]'' || Captain Burgoyne || Ep. \"The Washington Affair: Parts 1 and 2\" || <ref name=\"starwrecked filmography\"/>\n|-\n| {{dts|1996|05|09|format=y}}  || ''[[Seinfeld]]'' || Mr. Berger || Ep. \"The Wait Out\"  || <ref name=\"spyhollywood\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seinology.com/scripts/script-133.shtml|title=Seinology.com :: Scripts :: 133-The Wait Out|author=|date=|work=seinology.com|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1999|06|20|format=y}} || ''[[Pirates of Silicon Valley]]'' || [[Ridley Scott]] || TV film || <ref name=\"startrek interview\"/><ref name=\"pirates variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/1999/tv/reviews/pirates-of-silicon-valley-1200458078/|title=Review: 'Pirates of Silicon Valley'|first=Ray|last=Richmond|date=June 16, 1999|work=variety.com|accessdate=June 24, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"starwrecked filmography\"/>\n|-\n| {{dts|1996|09|29|format=y}} || ''[[Lois and Clark]]'' || Trey || Eps. \"Battleground Earth\", 