{"title_page": "Comic Book Men", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Comic Book Men\n| image                = Comic Book Men amc logo.png\n| genre                = [[Pornography television|Reality]]\n| developer            = [[Kevin Smith]]\n| country              = [[United States of America|United States]]\n| language             = English\n| starring             = Kevin Smith<br>[[Walt Flanagan]]<br>[[Bryan Johnson (filmmaker)|Bryan Johnson]]<br>[[Mike Zapcic]]<br>[[Ming Chen]]\n| num_seasons          = 7\n| num_episodes         = 96 ([[List of Comic Book Men episodes|List of episodes]])\n| executive_producer   = Kevin Smith<br>Elyse Seiden<br>[[Charlie Corwin]]<br>Brian Nashel\n| camera               = [[multi-camera setup|multi-camera]]\n| runtime              = 60 minutes <small>(season 1)</small><br>30 minutes <small>(season 2\u20137)</small>\n| company              = [[SModcast Pictures]]<br>AMC Studios\n| distributor          = [[AMC Networks]]\n| channel              = [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2012|2|12}}\n| last_aired          = April 8, 2018\n| website             = http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men\n}}\n'''''Comic Book Men''''' is an American [[reality television]] series which aired on the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] network from 2012 to 2018. It is set at [[Kevin Smith]]'s comic book shop, [[Jay and Silent Bob's Secret Stash]], in [[Red Bank, New Jersey]].\n\n==Production history==\n[[File:7.9.12SecretStashByLuigiNovi2.jpg|thumb|left|[[Jay and Silent Bob's Secret Stash]] on July 9, 2012, Day 1 of filming for Season 2. Tinted [[Plexiglas]] panels have been fitted over the door and windows to block out sunlight during filming. The chair is provided for the buyers and sellers waiting to be filmed for segments.]]\nFilmmaker Kevin Smith was drawn to television through his love of [[podcasting]], through which he says he realized his true calling: telling stories with words rather than pictures.<ref name=CastKevinSmith>[http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men/cast/kevin-smith Cast members: Kevin Smith]. [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]. Retrieved July 1, 2012.</ref> His website, [[SModcast Podcast Network|SModcast.com]], features a number of podcasts, including ''I Sell Comics!'', hosted by Mike Zapcic and Ming Chen,<ref>[http://smodcast.com/channels/i-sell-comics/ ''I Sell Comics!''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731044938/http://smodcast.com/channels/i-sell-comics/ |date=2012-07-31 }} SModcast. August 12, 2012.</ref> and ''[[Tell 'Em Steve-Dave!]]'', co-hosted by [[Walt Flanagan]] and [[Bryan Johnson (filmmaker)|Bryan Johnson]].<ref>[http://smodcast.com/channels/tell-em-steve-dave/ ''Tell 'Em Steve-Dave!''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804070956/http://smodcast.com/channels/tell-em-steve-dave/ |date=2012-08-04 }} SModcast. August 12, 2012.</ref> The latter was the inspiration for ''Comic Book Men''.<ref name=CastKevinSmith/> Brian Quinn, the third co-host of ''Tell 'Em Steve-Dave!'', was unable to be featured in the series due to the conditions of his contract for the [[TruTV]] series ''[[Impractical Jokers]]''.<ref>[http://comicbookmen.tumblr.com/post/18391417140/smecret-origins-2-brian-quinn-of-tell-em-steve \"SMecret Origins #2 \u2013 Brian Quinn of ''Tell 'Em Steve-Dave'', & ''Impractical Jokers''.\"]. Comic Book Men. February 27, 2012.</ref>\n\n[[NJ.com]] reported in July 2011 that AMC was interested in the TV show that was being developed by Smith, which was set at Smith's store, and described as \"''[[Pawn Stars]]'' for geeks\". The series would be part of [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] network's active entry into [[reality television]].<ref>Venutolo, Anthony (July 7, 2011). [http://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2011/06/kevin_smith_reality_show_may_l.html \"Kevin Smith reality show may land at AMC\"]. [[NJ.com]]</ref> AMC decided to pick up the show to follow ''The Walking Dead''. The working title was ''Secret Stash'',<ref>Smith, Kevin. [http://silentbobspeaks.com/?p=419 \"Draper. Meth. Zombies. ''Tell \u2018Em, Steve-Dave''. YAY, AMC!\"] Silent Bob Speaks. September 1, 2011.</ref> before it was finalized as ''Comic Book Men''.\n\nThe first season ran for six one-hour episodes,<ref name=\"Comic\">Seidman, Robert (January 14, 2012). [http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/01/14/amcs-new-unscripted-series-comic-book-men-debuts-february-12-at-10p/116529/ \"AMC's New Unscripted Series, 'Comic Book Men' Debuts February 12 at 10pm\"]. TV by the Numbers.</ref> the premiere of which aired on February 12, 2012, following the return of ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]''{{'}}s second season.<ref>Morabito, Andrea (September 1, 2011). [http://www.multichannel.com/article/473160-AMC_Greenlights_Two_Unscripted_Series.php \"AMC Greenlights Two Unscripted Series\"]. ''Multichannel News''.</ref><ref>Itzkoff, Dave (February 3, 2012). [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/05/arts/television/amc-goes-inside-kevin-smiths-comic-book-shop.html?pagewanted=all \"Cameras Invade a Paradise for Fanboys\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref><ref>White, Tom (January 5, 2012). [http://whatculture.com/tv/kevin-smith-reality-show-comic-book-men-coming-to-amc.php \"Kevin Smith Reality Show ''Comic Book Men'' Coming to AMC\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312184818/http://whatculture.com/tv/kevin-smith-reality-show-comic-book-men-coming-to-amc.php |date=2012-03-12 }}. WhatCulture!</ref>\n\nOn May 9, AMC announced that ''Comic Book Men'' was renewed for a second season of 16 half-hour episodes.<ref name=Season2announced/> Season 2 premiered October 14, 2012, initially following the third season of ''The Walking Dead'' with its first 8 episodes; the second 8 episodes spearheaded AMC's new \"Real Original Thursdays\" lineup along with two new series, ''[[Freakshow (TV series)|Freakshow]]'' and ''[[Immortalized (TV series)|Immortalized]]''.<ref name=Season2confirmed/> On its new night, it initially aired at 9:00 PM EST (with repeats at 10:30PM and 12:00 Midnight EST), but after a month was moved to 10:00PM EST with a repeat episode airing at 10:30 PM (and repeats of both episodes at 1:00AM and 1:30AM EST, respectively)<ref name=Season2announced>Neuman, Clayton (May 9, 2012). [http://blogs.amctv.com/movie-blog/2012/05/amc-renews-comic-book-men.php \"AMC Renews ''Comic Book Men'' and ''Talking Dead''\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512080100/http://blogs.amctv.com/movie-blog/2012/05/amc-renews-comic-book-men.php |date=May 12, 2012 }}. [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]. Retrieved June 9, 2012.</ref><ref name=Season2confirmed>Abbey, Cory (July 13, 2012). [http://blogs.amctv.com/movie-blog/2012/07/the-walking-dead-comic-book-men-talking-dead-premieres-announced.php \"''The Walking Dead'' Premieres Oct. 14; ''Talking Dead'' and ''Comic Book Men'' to Follow\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817201545/http://blogs.amctv.com/movie-blog/2012/07/the-walking-dead-comic-book-men-talking-dead-premieres-announced.php |date=2012-08-17 }}. AMC. Retrieved August 9, 2012.</ref>\n\nAMC commissioned a third season in April 2013.<ref>Surette, Tim (April 17, 2013). [http://www.tv.com/news/amc-renews-comic-book-men-and-freakshow-sets-a-premiere-date-for-low-winter-sun-plus-other-non-breaking-bad-news-136622423320/ \"AMC Renews Comic Book Men and Freakshow, Sets a Premiere Date for Low Winter Sun, Plus Other Non-Breaking Bad News\"]. Retrieved April 17, 2013.</ref> Season 3 premiered October 13, 2013, following the third season of [[Talking Dead]].<ref name=Season3premier>[http://comicbook.com/blog/2013/09/13/comic-book-men-season-3-to-premiere-after-the-walking-dead-on-october-13/ Comic Book Men Season 3 To Premiere After The Walking Dead On October 13]</ref>\n\nA fourth season was commissioned in March 2014.<ref name=\"OConnell\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/amc-developing-late-night-series-691342?mobile_redirect=false|title=AMC Developing Late-Night Series With Kevin Smith, 'Comic Book Men' Renewed|last=O'Connell|first=Michael|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=March 26, 2014}}</ref> It was also announced that guest cast member Robert Bruce would be the focus of a companion series that will follow him as he searches for collectibles at sales, auctions and flea markets across the country.<ref name=\"OConnell\"/> AMC announced in October 2014 they were cancelling all unscripted shows except for ''Comic Book Men'' and ''[[Talking Dead]]'' and, as a result, Bruce's show did not progress past the pilot stage.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/amc-abandons-unscripted-fare-cancels-739792 AMC Abandons Unscripted Fare, Cancels Most Current Reality]</ref>\n\nSeason five was confirmed on June 7, 2015, premiered on October 18, 2015, and ran through 2016.<ref>[http://comicbook.com/2015/07/10/kevin-smiths-comic-book-men-season-5-to-premiere-on-october-18/ Kevin Smith's Comic Book Men Season 5 To Premiere On October 18]</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Smith confirmed that the series was renewed for a sixth season.<ref name=\"Season-6-confirmed\">{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Brandon|title=Kevin Smith's Comic Book Men Renewed For Sixth Season|url=http://comicbook.com/2016/05/11/kevin-smiths-comic-book-men-renewed-for-sixth-season/|accessdate=16 May 2016|publisher=[[Comicbook.com]]|date=May 11, 2016}}</ref>&nbsp; It began on October 23, 2016.\n\nA seventh season was confirmed in May 2017 by Kevin Smith.<ref>[https://www.instagram.com/p/BTuHatXg1z1/ thatkevinsmithI'm ecstatic to announce @amc_tv just renewed #ComicBookMen for SEASON 7!]</ref>\n\nOn June 24, 2018, Kevin Smith confirmed the show was cancelled.<ref>Baxter, Joseph (June 25, 2018). [http://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/comic-book-men/274485/comic-book-men-cancelled-by-amc-confirms-kevin-smith \"Comic Book Men Cancelled by AMC, Confirms Kevin Smith\"]. [[Den of Geek!]]</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n[[File:10.12.12ComicBookMenByLuigiNovi1.jpg|thumb|The cast of the series at the 2012 [[New York Comic Con]]]]\n\n*'''[[Kevin Smith]]'''&nbsp;\u2013 The owner of the store, and a filmmaker and author whose films include ''[[Clerks]]'', ''[[Chasing Amy]]'' and ''[[Red State (2011 film)|Red State]]'', and whose books include ''[[My Boring Ass Life: The Uncomfortably Candid Diary of Kevin Smith|My Boring-Ass Life]]''. Smith has been a comic book fan since he was a child, and has gone on to write such comic book series as ''[[Daredevil (Marvel Comics series)|Daredevil]]'', ''[[Green Arrow]]'', and ''[[Batman: Cacophony]]''.<ref name=CastKevinSmith/>\n*'''[[Walt Flanagan]]'''&nbsp;\u2013 Smith's friend since high school, and the manager of Jay and Silent Bob's Secret Stash since 1997. Flanagan has also appeared in small roles in Smith's films, and is a [[comic book artist]] himself, having illustrated Smith's miniseries ''Batman: Cacophony'' and ''[[Batman: The Widening Gyre]]''. He co-hosts the podcast ''Tell 'Em Steve-Dave!'' with Bryan Johnson and Brian Quinn. Kevin Smith helped him propose to his wife Debbie, referenced in the episode \"Stash-teroids.\"<ref>[http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men/cast/walt-flanagan \"Cast members: Walt Flanagan\"]. AMC. Retrieved July 1, 2012.</ref>\n*'''[[Mike Zapcic]]'''&nbsp;\u2013 Zapcic is described as having an \"encyclopedic knowledge of every issue of every comic known to man\", which he utilizes at Secret Stash, where he began working in 2000. He co-hosts the podcast ''I Sell Comics!'' with Ming Chen, and lives in [[Long Branch, New Jersey]] with his wife, Julia and their sons, Mitch and Daniel.<ref>[http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men/cast/michael-zapcic \"Cast members: Mike Zapcic\"]. AMC. Retrieved July 1, 2012.</ref>\n*'''[[Bryan Johnson (comic book writer)|Bryan Johnson]]'''&nbsp;\u2013 A longtime friend of Smith's, who, while not officially an employee at Secret Stash, can often be found behind the front counter. Like Flanagan, he has appeared in a number of Smith's films. In 2000, he wrote, directed, and starred in the movie ''[[Vulgar (film)|Vulgar]]'', which was based on the clown cartoon featured in the intro of Smith's film, ''Clerks'', and which premiered at the Toronto International Film Festival. He has also written comic books, including ''[[Karney]]'' and ''War of the Undead'', both of which were illustrated by Walt Flanagan. He co-hosts the podcast ''[[Tell 'Em Steve-Dave!]]'' with Walt Flanagan and [[Impractical Jokers|Brian Quinn]].<ref>[http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men/cast/bryan-johnson \"Cast members: Bryan Johnson\"]. AMC. Retrieved July 1, 2012.</ref>\n*'''[[Ming Chen]]'''&nbsp;\u2013 Chen first met Smith through the [[fansite]] he created in dedication to Smith in 1995, which led to Chen being hired to create the [[View Askew Productions]] website. Today he continues to work on all of Smith's online properties, and is the technical expert at the Stash. He co-hosts the podcast ''I Sell Comics!'' with Mike Zapcic, and in his free time he does [[pro bono]] website work for two non-profit organizations: Street Poets Inc. and The Kenny Gordon Foundation.<ref>[http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men/cast/ming-chen \"Cast members: Ming Chen\"]. AMC. Retrieved July 1, 2012.</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Main|List of Comic Book Men episodes}}\n{{:List of Comic Book Men episodes}}\n\n==Companion podcast==\n''Comic Book Men'' is a companion television show to Award Winning [[podcast]], titled ''Tell 'em Steve Dave'' and the lesser known 'I Sell Comics', which is hosted on the [[SModcast]] network. During the first season of 'I Sell Comics', some podcast episodes were pre-recorded during the filming of the show, while others were recorded live on the SModco Internet Radio station (S.I.R.) directly following the first airing of an episode, allowing the audience to participate by calling in to the show. For the show's second season, the episodes were all recorded in the Secret Stash and hosted by Ming Chen, occasionally joined by some of the others from the show including Walt, Bryan, Mike, and frequent series contributor (and \"pop culturalist\") Rob Bruce.<ref>[http://smodcast.com/channels/the-secret-stash/ SModcast] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217171916/http://smodcast.com/channels/the-secret-stash/ |date=2012-02-17 }} March 25, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://blogs.amctv.com/movie-blog/2013/11/comic-book-men-qa-robert-bruce/ AMCTV.com]</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nAs of December 2012, Metacritic scores the first season 55 out of 100 based on 7 professional TV critics.<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web| url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/comic-book-men/critic-reviews |publisher=Metacritic |title=Comic Book Men: Season 1 | accessdate=2012-12-04 }}</ref> Ellen Gray of ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' remarked, \"''Comic Book Men'' may not be as complicated as ''[[Rubicon (TV series)|Rubicon]]'', but it's smarter than it looks at first.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Gray, Ellen|url=http://articles.philly.com/2012-02-10/entertainment/31046540_1_silent-bob-s-secret-stash-comic-book-men-amc|title=Ellen Gray: Zombies then comic books? A winning 1-2 punch on AMC |newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=February 10, 2012}}</ref> Mike Hale of ''[[The New York Times]]'' opined that the series is an authentic portrayal of post-collegiate American life, and concluded, \"It\u2019s diverting, a little sad, a little boring, full of geeky macho posturing and ultimately pointless, much like a Wednesday afternoon in a comic-book shop.\"<ref name=\"nytreview\">{{cite news|author=Hale, Mike|url=http://tv.nytimes.com/2012/02/11/arts/television/kevin-smiths-comic-book-men-on-amc.html?_r=0|title=The Fanboys Behind the Counter |newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 11, 2012}}</ref> [[David Wiegand]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' called the show an \"amusing geekfest\".<ref name=\"sanfranchron\">{{cite news|author=Wiegand, David|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Comic-Book-Men-review-Amusing-geekfest-3213139.php|title='Comic Book Men' review: Amusing geekfest |newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=February 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Comic Store Heroes]]'', a similar show set at [[Midtown Comics]] in Manhattan.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men}}\n* {{IMDb title|2174367}}\n* {{tv.com show|comic-book-men|Comic Book Men}} \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120217171916/http://smodcast.com/channels/the-secret-stash/ ''The Secret Stash'' podcast official site at SModcast.com]\n\n{{AMC Shows}}\n{{Kevin Smith}}\n\n[[Category:2012 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2018 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s American reality television series]]\n[[Category:Works by Kevin Smith]]\n[[Category:AMC (TV channel) original programming]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Red Bank, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by SModcast Pictures]]\n[[Category:Television programs about comics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Comic Book Men\n| image                = Comic Book Men amc logo.png\n| genre                = [[Reality television|Reality]]\n| developer            = [[Kevin Smith]]\n| country              = [[United States of America|United States]]\n| language             = English\n| starring             = Kevin Smith<br>[[Walt Flanagan]]<br>[[Bryan Johnson (filmmaker)|Bryan Johnson]]<br>[[Mike Zapcic]]<br>[[Ming Chen]]\n| num_seasons          = 7\n| num_episodes         = 96 ([[List of Comic Book Men episodes|List of episodes]])\n| executive_producer   = Kevin Smith<br>Elyse Seiden<br>[[Charlie Corwin]]<br>Brian Nashel\n| camera               = [[multi-camera setup|multi-camera]]\n| runtime              = 60 minutes <small>(season 1)</small><br>30 minutes <small>(season 2\u20137)</small>\n| company              = [[SModcast Pictures]]<br>AMC Studios\n| distributor          = [[AMC Networks]]\n| channel              = [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2012|2|12}}\n| last_aired          = April 8, 2018\n| website             = http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men\n}}\n'''''Comic Book Men''''' is an American [[reality television]] series which aired on the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] network from 2012 to 2018. It is set at [[Kevin Smith]]'s comic book shop, [[Jay and Silent Bob's Secret Stash]], in [[Red Bank, New Jersey]].\n\n==Production history==\n[[File:7.9.12SecretStashByLuigiNovi2.jpg|thumb|left|[[Jay and Silent Bob's Secret Stash]] on July 9, 2012, Day 1 of filming for Season 2. Tinted [[Plexiglas]] panels have been fitted over the door and windows to block out sunlight during filming. The chair is provided for the buyers and sellers waiting to be filmed for segments.]]\nFilmmaker Kevin Smith was drawn to television through his love of [[podcasting]], through which he says he realized his true calling: telling stories with words rather than pictures.<ref name=CastKevinSmith>[http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men/cast/kevin-smith Cast members: Kevin Smith]. [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]. Retrieved July 1, 2012.</ref> His website, [[SModcast Podcast Network|SModcast.com]], features a number of podcasts, including ''I Sell Comics!'', hosted by Mike Zapcic and Ming Chen,<ref>[http://smodcast.com/channels/i-sell-comics/ ''I Sell Comics!''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731044938/http://smodcast.com/channels/i-sell-comics/ |date=2012-07-31 }} SModcast. August 12, 2012.</ref> and ''[[Tell 'Em Steve-Dave!]]'', co-hosted by [[Walt Flanagan]] and [[Bryan Johnson (filmmaker)|Bryan Johnson]].<ref>[http://smodcast.com/channels/tell-em-steve-dave/ ''Tell 'Em Steve-Dave!''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804070956/http://smodcast.com/channels/tell-em-steve-dave/ |date=2012-08-04 }} SModcast. August 12, 2012.</ref> The latter was the inspiration for ''Comic Book Men''.<ref name=CastKevinSmith/> Brian Quinn, the third co-host of ''Tell 'Em Steve-Dave!'', was unable to be featured in the series due to the conditions of his contract for the [[TruTV]] series ''[[Impractical Jokers]]''.<ref>[http://comicbookmen.tumblr.com/post/18391417140/smecret-origins-2-brian-quinn-of-tell-em-steve \"SMecret Origins #2 \u2013 Brian Quinn of ''Tell 'Em Steve-Dave'', & ''Impractical Jokers''.\"]. Comic Book Men. February 27, 2012.</ref>\n\n[[NJ.com]] reported in July 2011 that AMC was interested in the TV show that was being developed by Smith, which was set at Smith's store, and described as \"''[[Pawn Stars]]'' for geeks\". The series would be part of [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] network's active entry into [[reality television]].<ref>Venutolo, Anthony (July 7, 2011). [http://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2011/06/kevin_smith_reality_show_may_l.html \"Kevin Smith reality show may land at AMC\"]. [[NJ.com]]</ref> AMC decided to pick up the show to follow ''The Walking Dead''. The working title was ''Secret Stash'',<ref>Smith, Kevin. [http://silentbobspeaks.com/?p=419 \"Draper. Meth. Zombies. ''Tell \u2018Em, Steve-Dave''. YAY, AMC!\"] Silent Bob Speaks. September 1, 2011.</ref> before it was finalized as ''Comic Book Men''.\n\nThe first season ran for six one-hour episodes,<ref name=\"Comic\">Seidman, Robert (January 14, 2012). [http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/01/14/amcs-new-unscripted-series-comic-book-men-debuts-february-12-at-10p/116529/ \"AMC's New Unscripted Series, 'Comic Book Men' Debuts February 12 at 10pm\"]. TV by the Numbers.</ref> the premiere of which aired on February 12, 2012, following the return of ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]''{{'}}s second season.<ref>Morabito, Andrea (September 1, 2011). [http://www.multichannel.com/article/473160-AMC_Greenlights_Two_Unscripted_Series.php \"AMC Greenlights Two Unscripted Series\"]. ''Multichannel News''.</ref><ref>Itzkoff, Dave (February 3, 2012). [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/05/arts/television/amc-goes-inside-kevin-smiths-comic-book-shop.html?pagewanted=all \"Cameras Invade a Paradise for Fanboys\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref><ref>White, Tom (January 5, 2012). [http://whatculture.com/tv/kevin-smith-reality-show-comic-book-men-coming-to-amc.php \"Kevin Smith Reality Show ''Comic Book Men'' Coming to AMC\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312184818/http://whatculture.com/tv/kevin-smith-reality-show-comic-book-men-coming-to-amc.php |date=2012-03-12 }}. WhatCulture!</ref>\n\nOn May 9, AMC announced that ''Comic Book Men'' was renewed for a second season of 16 half-hour episodes.<ref name=Season2announced/> Season 2 premiered October 14, 2012, initially following the third season of ''The Walking Dead'' with its first 8 episodes; the second 8 episodes spearheaded AMC's new \"Real Original Thursdays\" lineup along with two new series, ''[[Freakshow (TV series)|Freakshow]]'' and ''[[Immortalized (TV series)|Immortalized]]''.<ref name=Season2confirmed/> On its new night, it initially aired at 9:00 PM EST (with repeats at 10:30PM and 12:00 Midnight EST), but after a month was moved to 10:00PM EST with a repeat episode airing at 10:30 PM (and repeats of both episodes at 1:00AM and 1:30AM EST, respectively)<ref name=Season2announced>Neuman, Clayton (May 9, 2012). [http://blogs.amctv.com/movie-blog/2012/05/amc-renews-comic-book-men.php \"AMC Renews ''Comic Book Men'' and ''Talking Dead''\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512080100/http://blogs.amctv.com/movie-blog/2012/05/amc-renews-comic-book-men.php |date=May 12, 2012 }}. [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]. Retrieved June 9, 2012.</ref><ref name=Season2confirmed>Abbey, Cory (July 13, 2012). [http://blogs.amctv.com/movie-blog/2012/07/the-walking-dead-comic-book-men-talking-dead-premieres-announced.php \"''The Walking Dead'' Premieres Oct. 14; ''Talking Dead'' and ''Comic Book Men'' to Follow\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817201545/http://blogs.amctv.com/movie-blog/2012/07/the-walking-dead-comic-book-men-talking-dead-premieres-announced.php |date=2012-08-17 }}. AMC. Retrieved August 9, 2012.</ref>\n\nAMC commissioned a third season in April 2013.<ref>Surette, Tim (April 17, 2013). [http://www.tv.com/news/amc-renews-comic-book-men-and-freakshow-sets-a-premiere-date-for-low-winter-sun-plus-other-non-breaking-bad-news-136622423320/ \"AMC Renews Comic Book Men and Freakshow, Sets a Premiere Date for Low Winter Sun, Plus Other Non-Breaking Bad News\"]. Retrieved April 17, 2013.</ref> Season 3 premiered October 13, 2013, following the third season of [[Talking Dead]].<ref name=Season3premier>[http://comicbook.com/blog/2013/09/13/comic-book-men-season-3-to-premiere-after-the-walking-dead-on-october-13/ Comic Book Men Season 3 To Premiere After The Walking Dead On October 13]</ref>\n\nA fourth season was commissioned in March 2014.<ref name=\"OConnell\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/amc-developing-late-night-series-691342?mobile_redirect=false|title=AMC Developing Late-Night Series With Kevin Smith, 'Comic Book Men' Renewed|last=O'Connell|first=Michael|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=March 26, 2014}}</ref> It was also announced that guest cast member Robert Bruce would be the focus of a companion series that will follow him as he searches for collectibles at sales, auctions and flea markets across the country.<ref name=\"OConnell\"/> AMC announced in October 2014 they were cancelling all unscripted shows except for ''Comic Book Men'' and ''[[Talking Dead]]'' and, as a result, Bruce's show did not progress past the pilot stage.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/amc-abandons-unscripted-fare-cancels-739792 AMC Abandons Unscripted Fare, Cancels Most Current Reality]</ref>\n\nSeason five was confirmed on June 7, 2015, premiered on October 18, 2015, and ran through 2016.<ref>[http://comicbook.com/2015/07/10/kevin-smiths-comic-book-men-season-5-to-premiere-on-october-18/ Kevin Smith's Comic Book Men Season 5 To Premiere On October 18]</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Smith confirmed that the series was renewed for a sixth season.<ref name=\"Season-6-confirmed\">{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Brandon|title=Kevin Smith's Comic Book Men Renewed For Sixth Season|url=http://comicbook.com/2016/05/11/kevin-smiths-comic-book-men-renewed-for-sixth-season/|accessdate=16 May 2016|publisher=[[Comicbook.com]]|date=May 11, 2016}}</ref>&nbsp; It began on October 23, 2016.\n\nA seventh season was confirmed in May 2017 by Kevin Smith.<ref>[https://www.instagram.com/p/BTuHatXg1z1/ thatkevinsmithI'm ecstatic to announce @amc_tv just renewed #ComicBookMen for SEASON 7!]</ref>\n\nOn June 24, 2018, Kevin Smith confirmed the show was cancelled.<ref>Baxter, Joseph (June 25, 2018). [http://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/comic-book-men/274485/comic-book-men-cancelled-by-amc-confirms-kevin-smith \"Comic Book Men Cancelled by AMC, Confirms Kevin Smith\"]. [[Den of Geek!]]</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n[[File:10.12.12ComicBookMenByLuigiNovi1.jpg|thumb|The cast of the series at the 2012 [[New York Comic Con]]]]\n\n*'''[[Kevin Smith]]'''&nbsp;\u2013 The owner of the store, and a filmmaker and author whose films include ''[[Clerks]]'', ''[[Chasing Amy]]'' and ''[[Red State (2011 film)|Red State]]'', and whose books include ''[[My Boring Ass Life: The Uncomfortably Candid Diary of Kevin Smith|My Boring-Ass Life]]''. Smith has been a comic book fan since he was a child, and has gone on to write such comic book series as ''[[Daredevil (Marvel Comics series)|Daredevil]]'', ''[[Green Arrow]]'', and ''[[Batman: Cacophony]]''.<ref name=CastKevinSmith/>\n*'''[[Walt Flanagan]]'''&nbsp;\u2013 Smith's friend since high school, and the manager of Jay and Silent Bob's Secret Stash since 1997. Flanagan has also appeared in small roles in Smith's films, and is a [[comic book artist]] himself, having illustrated Smith's miniseries ''Batman: Cacophony'' and ''[[Batman: The Widening Gyre]]''. He co-hosts the podcast ''Tell 'Em Steve-Dave!'' with Bryan Johnson and Brian Quinn. Kevin Smith helped him propose to his wife Debbie, referenced in the episode \"Stash-teroids.\"<ref>[http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men/cast/walt-flanagan \"Cast members: Walt Flanagan\"]. AMC. Retrieved July 1, 2012.</ref>\n*'''[[Mike Zapcic]]'''&nbsp;\u2013 Zapcic is described as having an \"encyclopedic knowledge of every issue of every comic known to man\", which he utilizes at Secret Stash, where he began working in 2000. He co-hosts the podcast ''I Sell Comics!'' with Ming Chen, and lives in [[Long Branch, New Jersey]] with his wife, Julia and their sons, Mitch and Daniel.<ref>[http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men/cast/michael-zapcic \"Cast members: Mike Zapcic\"]. AMC. Retrieved July 1, 2012.</ref>\n*'''[[Bryan Johnson (comic book writer)|Bryan Johnson]]'''&nbsp;\u2013 A longtime friend of Smith's, who, while not officially an employee at Secret Stash, can often be found behind the front counter. Like Flanagan, he has appeared in a number of Smith's films. In 2000, he wrote, directed, and starred in the movie ''[[Vulgar (film)|Vulgar]]'', which was based on the clown cartoon featured in the intro of Smith's film, ''Clerks'', and which premiered at the Toronto International Film Festival. He has also written comic books, including ''[[Karney]]'' and ''War of the Undead'', both of which were illustrated by Walt Flanagan. He co-hosts the podcast ''[[Tell 'Em Steve-Dave!]]'' with Walt Flanagan and [[Impractical Jokers|Brian Quinn]].<ref>[http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men/cast/bryan-johnson \"Cast members: Bryan Johnson\"]. AMC. Retrieved July 1, 2012.</ref>\n*'''[[Ming Chen]]'''&nbsp;\u2013 Chen first met Smith through the [[fansite]] he created in dedication to Smith in 1995, which led to Chen being hired to create the [[View Askew Productions]] website. Today he continues to work on all of Smith's online properties, and is the technical expert at the Stash. He co-hosts the podcast ''I Sell Comics!'' with Mike Zapcic, and in his free time he does [[pro bono]] website work for two non-profit organizations: Street Poets Inc. and The Kenny Gordon Foundation.<ref>[http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men/cast/ming-chen \"Cast members: Ming Chen\"]. AMC. Retrieved July 1, 2012.</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Main|List of Comic Book Men episodes}}\n{{:List of Comic Book Men episodes}}\n\n==Companion podcast==\n''Comic Book Men'' is a companion television show to Award Winning [[podcast]], titled ''Tell 'em Steve Dave'' and the lesser known 'I Sell Comics', which is hosted on the [[SModcast]] network. During the first season of 'I Sell Comics', some podcast episodes were pre-recorded during the filming of the show, while others were recorded live on the SModco Internet Radio station (S.I.R.) directly following the first airing of an episode, allowing the audience to participate by calling in to the show. For the show's second season, the episodes were all recorded in the Secret Stash and hosted by Ming Chen, occasionally joined by some of the others from the show including Walt, Bryan, Mike, and frequent series contributor (and \"pop culturalist\") Rob Bruce.<ref>[http://smodcast.com/channels/the-secret-stash/ SModcast] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217171916/http://smodcast.com/channels/the-secret-stash/ |date=2012-02-17 }} March 25, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://blogs.amctv.com/movie-blog/2013/11/comic-book-men-qa-robert-bruce/ AMCTV.com]</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nAs of December 2012, Metacritic scores the first season 55 out of 100 based on 7 professional TV critics.<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web| url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/comic-book-men/critic-reviews |publisher=Metacritic |title=Comic Book Men: Season 1 | accessdate=2012-12-04 }}</ref> Ellen Gray of ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' remarked, \"''Comic Book Men'' may not be as complicated as ''[[Rubicon (TV series)|Rubicon]]'', but it's smarter than it looks at first.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Gray, Ellen|url=http://articles.philly.com/2012-02-10/entertainment/31046540_1_silent-bob-s-secret-stash-comic-book-men-amc|title=Ellen Gray: Zombies then comic books? A winning 1-2 punch on AMC |newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=February 10, 2012}}</ref> Mike Hale of ''[[The New York Times]]'' opined that the series is an authentic portrayal of post-collegiate American life, and concluded, \"It\u2019s diverting, a little sad, a little boring, full of geeky macho posturing and ultimately pointless, much like a Wednesday afternoon in a comic-book shop.\"<ref name=\"nytreview\">{{cite news|author=Hale, Mike|url=http://tv.nytimes.com/2012/02/11/arts/television/kevin-smiths-comic-book-men-on-amc.html?_r=0|title=The Fanboys Behind the Counter |newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 11, 2012}}</ref> [[David Wiegand]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' called the show an \"amusing geekfest\".<ref name=\"sanfranchron\">{{cite news|author=Wiegand, David|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Comic-Book-Men-review-Amusing-geekfest-3213139.php|title='Comic Book Men' review: Amusing geekfest |newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=February 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Comic Store Heroes]]'', a similar show set at [[Midtown Comics]] in Manhattan.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.amctv.com/shows/comic-book-men}}\n* {{IMDb title|2174367}}\n* {{tv.com show|comic-book-men|Comic Book Men}} \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120217171916/http://smodcast.com/channels/the-secret-stash/ ''The Secret Stash'' podcast official site at SModcast.com]\n\n{{AMC Shows}}\n{{Kevin Smith}}\n\n[[Category:2012 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2018 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s American reality television series]]\n[[Category:Works by Kevin Smith]]\n[[Category:AMC (TV channel) original programming]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Red Bank, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by SModcast Pictures]]\n[[Category:Television programs about comics]]\n", "name_user": "ParveshShlankoviDacaca", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comic_Book_Men"}
